# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: brig
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:brig/a-drama-in-mexico] In 1825, off the islands of Guam on a passage from Spain, Lieutenant Martinez, and his associates plot a mutiny on board of two Spanish warships.
[src:brig/a-drama-in-mexico] Conspirators murder Captain Don Orteva, take command of the ships, and plan to sell them to the republican government in Mexico.
[src:brig/a-drama-in-mexico] On arrival in Acapulco, Lieutenant Martinez and Jose embark on a cross-country trip to Mexico City to effect the sale.
[src:brig/a-drama-in-mexico] Martinez becomes increasingly fearful that he is being pursued by Ortega's loyal followers, and during a stormy night in the mountains murders Jose in a moment of madness and is then toppled to his death in a mountain torrent by the men he feared.
[src:brig/a-drama-in-mexico] The story was originally published in French in July 1851 as "L'Amérique du Nord, études historiques: Les Premiers Navires de la marine mexicaine" in *Musée des familles* with three illustrations by Eugène Forest and Alexandre de Bar.
[src:brig/a-drama-in-mexico] A renamed and revised version, "Un drame au Mexique," with six illustrations by Jules Férat, was published in 1876 together with the novel *Michel Strogoff* as a part of the *Voyages Extraordinaires* series.
[src:brig/a-drama-in-mexico] Kingston was published in London in 1876.
[src:brig/a-drama-in-mexico] as "The Mutineers: A Romance of Mexico" (translated by W.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] 1620), also known as the **Age of Exploration**, was part of the early modern period and overlapped with the Age of Sail.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] It was a period from approximately the 15th to the 17th century, during which seafarers from European countries explored, colonized, and conquered regions across the globe.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] The Age of Discovery was a transformative period when previously isolated parts of the world became connected to form the world-system, and laid the groundwork for globalization.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] The extensive overseas exploration, particularly the opening of maritime routes to the East Indies and European colonization of the Americas by the Spaniards and Portuguese, later joined by the English, French, and Dutch, spurred international global trade.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] The interconnected global economy of the 21st century has its origins in the expansion of trade networks during this era.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] The exploration created European colonial empires and marked an increased adoption of colonialism as a government policy in several European states.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] As such, it is sometimes synonymous with the first wave of European colonization.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] This colonization reshaped power dynamics causing geopolitical shifts in Europe and creating new centers of power beyond Europe.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Portuguese oceanic exploration began with maritime expeditions to the Macaronesian islands, including the Canary Islands, as well as Madeira and the Azores.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] It continued with voyages along the coast of West Africa in 1434, and culminated in the establishment of a sea route to India in 1498 by Vasco da Gama, which initiated Portugal's maritime and commercial presence in Kerala and the Indian Ocean.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Spain also undertook other major early voyages, including the conquest of Mexico (1519–1521), the conquest of Peru (1532–1533), and the Manila galleon trade route (1565–1815), which linked the Americas and Asia across the Pacific.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] European exploration initiated the Columbian exchange between the Old World (Europe, Asia, and Africa) and New World (Americas).
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] This exchange involved the transfer of plants, animals, human populations (including slaves), communicable diseases, and culture across the Eastern and Western Hemispheres.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] The Age of Discovery and European exploration involved mapping the world, shaping a new worldview and facilitating contact with distant civilizations.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] The continents drawn by European mapmakers developed from abstract "blobs" into the outlines more recognizable to us.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Simultaneously, the spread of new diseases, especially affecting American Indians, led to rapid declines in some populations.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] The era saw widespread enslavement, exploitation and military conquest of Indigenous peoples, concurrent with the growing economic influence and spread of Western culture, science, and technology leading to a faster-than-exponential population growth world-wide.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] The concept of discovery has been scrutinized, critically highlighting the history of the core term of this periodization.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] The term "age of discovery" is in historical literature and still commonly used.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Something of which they had no prior knowledge had suddenly presented itself to their gaze." O'Gorman argues that the physical encounter with new territories was less important than the Europeans' effort to integrate this new knowledge into their worldview, what he calls "the invention of America".
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Pagden examines the origins of the terms "discovery" and "invention".
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] In English, "discovery" and its forms in romance languages derive from "*disco-operio*, meaning to uncover, to reveal, to expose to the gaze", what was revealed existed previously.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Few Europeans during the period used the term "invention" for the European encounters, with the exception of Martin Waldseemüller, whose map first used the term "America".
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] A central legal concept of the discovery doctrine, expounded by the United States Supreme Court in 1823, draws on assertions of European powers' right to claim land during their explorations.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] The concept of "discovery" has been used to enforce colonial claiming and discovery, but has been challenged by Indigenous peoples and researchers.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Many indigenous peoples have fundamentally challenged the concept of colonial claiming of "discovery" over their lands and people, as forced and negating indigenous presence.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] The period alternatively called the *Age of Exploration*, has been scrutinized through reflections on the exploration.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Its understanding and use, has been discussed as being framed and used for colonial ventures, discrimination and exploitation, by combining it with concepts such as the frontier (as in Frontier Thesis) and manifest destiny, up to the contemporary age of space exploration.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Alternatively, the term *contact*, as in first contact, has been used to shed more light on the age of discovery and colonialism, using the alternative names of *Age of Contact* or *Contact Period*, discussing it as an "unfinished, diverse project".
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] The Portuguese began systematically exploring the Atlantic coast of Africa in 1418, under the sponsorship of Prince Henry the Navigator.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1488, Bartolomeu Dias reached the Indian Ocean by this route.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1492, the Catholic Monarchs of Spain funded Genoese mariner Christopher Columbus's (Italian: *Cristoforo Colombo*) plan to sail west to reach the Indies, by crossing the Atlantic.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Columbus encountered a continent uncharted by Europeans (though it had been explored and temporarily colonized by the Norse 500 years earlier).
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Later, it was called America after Amerigo Vespucci, a trader working for Portugal.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Portugal quickly claimed those lands under the terms of the Treaty of Alcáçovas, but Castile was able to persuade the Pope, who was Castilian, to issue four papal bulls to divide the world into two regions of exploration, where each kingdom had exclusive rights to claim newly discovered lands.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] These were modified by the Treaty of Tordesillas, ratified by Pope Julius II.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1498, a Portuguese expedition commanded by Vasco da Gama reached India by sailing around Africa, opening up direct trade with Asia.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] The Portuguese sailed further eastward, to the valuable Spice Islands in 1512, landing in China one year later.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Japan was reached by the Portuguese in 1543.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1513, Spanish explorer Vasco Núñez de Balboa crossed the Isthmus of Panama and reached the "other sea" from the New World.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Thus, Europe first received news of the eastern and western Pacific within a one-year span around 1512.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] East and west exploration overlapped in 1522, when a Spanish expedition sailing westward, led by Portuguese navigator Ferdinand Magellan (and, after his death in what is now the Philippines, by navigator Juan Sebastián Elcano), completed the first circumnavigation of the world.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Spanish *conquistadors* explored the interior of the Americas, and some of the South Pacific islands.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Their main objective was to disrupt Portuguese trade in the East.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] From 1495, the French, English, and Dutch entered the race of exploration, after learning of Columbus' exploits, defying the Iberian monopoly on maritime trade by searching for new routes.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] The first expedition was led by John Cabot in 1497 to the north, in the service of England, followed by French expeditions to South America and later to North America.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Later expeditions went to the Pacific Ocean around South America, and eventually by following the Portuguese around Africa, into the Indian Ocean; discovering Australia in 1606, New Zealand in 1642, and Hawaii in 1778.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] From the 1580s to the 1640s, Russians explored and conquered almost the whole of Siberia, and claimed Alaska in the 1730s.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] After the fall of the Western Roman Empire largely severed the connection between Europe and lands further east, Christian Europe was largely a backwater compared to the Muslim world, which conquered and incorporated large territories in the Middle East and North Africa.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] The Christian Crusades to retake the Holy Land from the Muslims were not a military success, but they did bring Europe into contact with the Middle East and the valuable goods manufactured or traded there.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] From the 12th century, the European economy was transformed by the interconnecting of river and sea trade routes.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Economic growth of Iberia followed the Christian reconquest of Al-Andalus in what is now southern Spain and the siege of Lisbon (1147 AD), in Portugal.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] The decline of the Fatimid Caliphate's naval strength, which started before the First Crusade, helped the maritime Italian states, mainly Venice, Genoa and Pisa, dominate trade in the Eastern Mediterranean, with merchants there becoming wealthy and politically influential.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] The Norman conquest of England, in the late 11th century, allowed for peaceful trade on the North Sea.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] The Hanseatic League, a confederation of merchant guilds and their towns in north Germany, along the North Sea and Baltic Sea, was instrumental in the commercial development of the region.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] In the 12th century, the regions of Flanders, Hainault, and Brabant produced the finest quality textiles in northwest Europe, which encouraged merchants from Genoa and Venice to sail there from the Mediterranean, through the Strait of Gibraltar, and up the Atlantic coast.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Nicolòzzo Spinola made the first recorded direct voyage from Genoa to Flanders in 1277.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Technological advancements that were important to the Age of Exploration were the adoption of the magnetic compass and advances in ship design.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] The compass was an addition to the ancient method of navigation based on sightings of the sun and stars.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] It was invented during the Chinese Han dynasty and had been used for navigation in China by the 11th century.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] It was adopted by Arab traders in the Indian Ocean.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] The compass spread to Europe by the late 12th or early 13th century.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Use of the compass for navigation in the Indian Ocean was first mentioned in 1232.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] The first mention of use of the compass in Europe was in 1180.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] The Europeans used a "dry" compass, with a needle on a pivot.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] The compass card was also a European invention.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] The ships of the Age of Discovery post-dated the fusion of the northern European and Mediterranean shipbuilding traditions.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Prior to the late 13th/early 14th centuries, northern European ships were typically clinker built, with a single mast setting a square sail and a centre-line rudder hung on the sternpost with pintles and gudgeons.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Their counterparts in the Mediterranean were built with carvel hulls, had one or more masts (depending on size) which set lateen sails, and were steered with quarter-rudders positioned on the side of the hull.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Trade, pilgrimage and war brought ships from each tradition into the other's region, ultimately leading to the copying of features that were new to each.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Over the early 14th century, square sails started to be used in the Mediterranean, with the mainmast setting square rig and the mizzen carrying a lateen sail.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] In the first two decades of the 15th century this arrangement was copied in northern Europe where, by the late 1430s, some ships were built with carvel hulls.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] The result of this merging of traditions was the full-rigged ship, a carvel hull with a sternpost-hung pintle-and-gudgeon rudder and three masts: the foremast and mainmast setting square sails and the mizzen a lateen sail.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Alongside this type of vessel, the caravel was used.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] This type was also carvel built with a sternpost-hung rudder but could be completely lateen rigged or have some square sails.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Very few wrecks of Age of Discovery ships have been found and archaeologically investigated.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] More is known about Roman and Greek ships of classical antiquity than those of this period.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] The caravel is particularly poorly understood, despite the number of "replicas" that have been constructed.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] However, a particular set of hull construction characteristics have been identified from wrecks of this time, referred to as Iberian Atlantic shipbuilding tradition.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] They are found in the Molasses Reef wreck, Highbourne Cay wreck, the Red Bay wreck and some sites in European waters.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] European medieval knowledge about Asia beyond the reach of the Byzantine Empire was sourced in partial reports, often obscured by legends, dating back from the conquests of Alexander the Great and successors.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Another source was the Radhanite Jewish trade networks of merchants established as go-betweens between Europe and the Muslim world during the time of the Crusader states.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] There were reports of great African Sahara, but the knowledge was limited for the Europeans, to the Mediterranean coast and little else, since the Arab blockade of North Africa precluded exploration inland.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Knowledge about the Atlantic African coast was fragmented and derived mainly from old Greek and Roman maps based on Carthaginian knowledge, including Roman exploration of Mauritania.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] The Red Sea was barely known and only trade links with the maritime republics, Venice especially, fostered the collection of accurate maritime knowledge.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Indian Ocean trade routes were sailed by Arab traders.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] By 1400, a Latin translation of Ptolemy's *Geographia* reached Italy from Constantinople.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] The rediscovery of Roman geographical knowledge was a revelation, both for map-making and worldview, although reinforcing the idea that the Indian Ocean was landlocked.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] A prelude to the Age of Discovery was a series of European expeditions crossing Eurasia by land in the late Middle Ages.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] The Mongols had threatened Europe, but Mongol states also unified much of Eurasia and, from 1206 on, the *Pax Mongolica* allowed safe trade routes and communication lines from the Middle East to China.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] The close Italian links to the Levant raised curiosity and commercial interest in countries which lay further east.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] There are a few accounts of merchants from North Africa and the Mediterranean, who traded in the Indian Ocean in late medieval times (see also Indo-Mediterranean § Medieval era).
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Christian embassies were sent as far as Karakorum during the Mongol invasions of the Levant, from which they gained a greater understanding of the world.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] The first of these travellers was Giovanni da Pian del Carpine, dispatched by Pope Innocent IV to the Great Khan, who journeyed to Mongolia and back from 1241 to 1247.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Russian prince Yaroslav of Vladimir, and his sons Alexander Nevsky and Andrey II of Vladimir, travelled to the Mongolian capital.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Though having strong political implications, their journeys left no detailed accounts.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Other travellers followed, like French André de Longjumeau and Flemish William of Rubruck, who reached China through Central Asia.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Marco Polo, a Venetian merchant, dictated an account of journeys throughout Asia from 1271 to 1295, describing being a guest at the Yuan dynasty court of Kublai Khan in *Travels*.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] The Muslim fleet guarding the Strait of Gibraltar was defeated by Genoa in 1291.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] In that year, the Genoese attempted their first Atlantic exploration when merchant brothers Vadino and Ugolino Vivaldi sailed from Genoa with two galleys, but disappeared off the Moroccan coast, feeding fears of oceanic travel.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] From 1325 to 1354, a Moroccan scholar from Tangier, Ibn Battuta, journeyed through North Africa, the Sahara desert, West Africa, Southern Europe, Eastern Europe, the Horn of Africa, the Middle East, and Asia, having reached China.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] After returning, he dictated an account to a scholar he met in Granada, *The Rihla* ("The Journey"), the unheralded source on his adventures.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Between 1357 and 1371, a book of supposed travels compiled by John Mandeville acquired popularity.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Despite the unreliable and often fantastical nature of its accounts, it was used as a reference for the East, Egypt, and the Levant in general, asserting the old belief that Jerusalem was the centre of the world.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Following the period of Timurid relations with Europe, in 1439, Niccolò de' Conti published an account of his travels as a Muslim merchant to India and Southeast Asia.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1466–1472, Russian merchant Afanasy Nikitin of Tver travelled to India, which he described in his book *A Journey Beyond the Three Seas*.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] These overland journeys had little immediate effect.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] The Mongol Empire collapsed almost as quickly as it formed and soon the route to the east became more difficult and dangerous.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] The Black Death of the 14th century also blocked travel and trade for a time.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Religion played a critical role in motivating European expansionism.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1487, Portuguese envoys Pero da Covilhã and Afonso de Paiva were sent on a covert mission to gather intelligence on a potential sea route to India and inquire about Prester John, a Nestorian patriarch and king, believed to rule over parts of the subcontinent.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Covilhã was warmly received upon his arrival in Ethiopia, but forbidden from leaving.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] During the Middle Ages, the spread of Christianity throughout Europe fueled the desire to sermonise in lands beyond.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] This evangelical effort became a significant part of the military conquests of European powers, like Portugal, Spain, and France, often leading to the conversion of indigenous peoples, voluntarily or forced.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Religious orders such as the Franciscans, Dominicans, Augustinians, and Jesuits partook in most missionary endeavours in the New World.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] By the late 16th and 17th centuries, the latter's presence increased as they sought to reassert their power and revive the Catholic culture of Europe, which had been damaged by the Reformation.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] The Chinese had wide connections through trade in Asia and been sailing to Arabia, East Africa, and Egypt since the Tang dynasty (AD 618–907).
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Between 1405 and 1421, the third Ming emperor Yongle sponsored long range tributary missions in the Indian Ocean under the command of admiral Zheng He.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] A large fleet of new junk ships was prepared for the international diplomatic expeditions.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] The largest of these junks—that the Chinese termed *bao chuan* (treasure ships)—may have measured 121 metres (397 ft), and thousands of sailors were involved.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] At least seven well-documented expeditions were launched, each bigger and more expensive than the last.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] The fleets visited Arabia, East Africa, India, Malay Archipelago, and Thailand (then called Siam), exchanging goods along the way.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] They presented gifts of gold, silver, porcelain, and silk; in return, received such novelties as ostriches, zebras, camels, ivory, and giraffes.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] After the emperor's death, Zheng He led a final expedition departing from Nanking in 1431 and returning to Beijing in 1433.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] It is likely this last expedition reached as far as Madagascar.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] The travels were reported by Ma Huan, a Muslim voyager and translator who accompanied Zheng He on three of the expeditions, his account published as the *Yingya Shenglan* (Overall Survey of the Ocean's Shores) (1433).
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] The voyages had a significant and lasting effect on the organization of a maritime network, using and creating nodes and conduits in its wake, thereby restructuring international and cross-cultural relationships and exchanges.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] It was especially impactful as no other polity had exerted naval dominance over all sectors of the Indian Ocean, prior to these voyages.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] The Ming promoted alternative nodes as a strategy to establish control over the network.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] For instance, due to Chinese involvement, ports such as Malacca (in Southeast Asia), Cochin (Malabar Coast), and Malindi (Swahili Coast) had grown as key alternatives to other established ports.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] The appearance of the Ming treasure fleet generated and intensified competition among contending polities and rivals, each seeking an alliance with the Ming.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] The expeditions developed into a maritime trade enterprise, with imperial control over local markets and court-monitored transactions, generating revenue for China and its partners.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] They boosted regional trade and production, caused a supply shock in Eurasia and led to price spikes in Europe in the early 15th century.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] The tributary relations promoted during the voyages manifested a trend toward cross-regional interconnections and early globalization in Asia and Africa.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Diplomatic relations were built on mutually beneficial maritime trade and China's strong naval presence in foreign waters, with Chinese naval superiority being a key factor in these interactions.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] The voyages brought about the Western Ocean's regional integration and increase in international circulation of people, ideas, and goods.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] It provided a platform for cosmopolitan discourses, which took place in locations such as the ships of the Ming treasure fleet, the Ming capitals of Nanjing as well as Beijing, and the banquet receptions organized by the Ming court for foreign representatives.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Diverse groups of people from maritime countries congregated, interacted, and traveled together as the treasure fleet sailed from and to China.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] For the first time, the maritime region from China to Africa was under the dominance of a single imperial power and allowed for the creation of a cosmopolitan space.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] These long-distance journeys were not followed up, as the Ming dynasty retreated in the *haijin*, a policy of isolationism, having limited maritime trade.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] From the 8th until the 15th century, the Republic of Venice and neighboring maritime republics held the monopoly of European trade with the Middle East.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] The silk and spice trade, involving spices, incense, herbs, drugs, and opium, made these Mediterranean city-states phenomenally rich.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Spices were among the most expensive and demanded products of the Middle Ages, as they were used in medieval medicine, religious rituals, cosmetics, perfumery, and food additives and preservatives.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] They were imported from Asia and Africa.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Muslim traders dominated maritime routes throughout the Indian Ocean, tapping source regions in the Far East and shipping for trading emporiums in India, mainly Calicut, westward to Hormuz in the Persian Gulf and Jeddah in the Red Sea.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] From there, overland routes led to the Mediterranean.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Afterwards, the routes into Asia through the Black Sea and through Armenia and Persia became blocked by wars and banditry as the Mongol states disintegrated.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] The trade route from the Persian Gulf to the Mediterranean by land is also dangerous due to the unstable territorial control of the Mamluk.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] The trade from India went almost entirely into the Red Sea.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Nevertheless, European spices have not become more expensive as a result.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Forced to reduce activity in the Black Sea, and at war with Venice, the Genoese had turned to North African trade of wheat, olive oil and a search for silver and gold.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Europeans had a constant deficit in silver and gold, as it only went out, spent on eastern trade now cut off.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Several European mines were exhausted, The lack of bullion led to the development of a complex banking system to manage the risks in trade (the first state bank, *Banco di San Giorgio*, was founded in 1407 at Genoa).
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Sailing into the ports of Bruges and England, Genoese communities were then established in Portugal, who profited from their enterprise and financial expertise.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] European sailing had been primarily close to land cabotage, guided by portolan charts.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] These charts specified proven ocean routes guided by coastal landmarks: sailors departed from a known point, followed a compass heading, and tried to identify their location by its landmarks.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] For the first oceanic exploration Europeans used the compass, and advances in cartography and astronomy.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Arab navigational tools like the astrolabe and quadrant were used for celestial navigation.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] The Muslim lands in Asia were more economically developed, had better infrastructure, despite Europe's economic changes brought by the Black Death, allowing for more freedoms.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] The Islamic gunpowder empires concealed knowledge from European Christian traders about where lucrative locations such as Indonesia were.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1317, King Denis of Portugal made an agreement with Genoese merchant sailor Manuel Pessanha, appointing him first admiral of the Portuguese Navy, to defend the country against Muslim pirate raids.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Outbreaks of bubonic plague led to depopulation in the second half of the 14th century: only the sea offered alternatives, with most population settling in fishing and trading coastal areas.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Between 1325 and 1357, Afonso IV of Portugal encouraged maritime commerce and ordered the first explorations.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] The Canary Islands, already known to the Genoese, were claimed as officially discovered under the patronage of the Portuguese, but in 1344, Castile disputed them.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] To ensure their trade monopoly, Europeans, beginning with the Portuguese, attempted to install a Mediterranean system of trade which used military intimidation, to divert trade through ports they controlled; there it could be taxed.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1415, Ceuta, in North Africa, was conquered by the Portuguese aiming to control navigation of the African coast.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Young prince Henry the Navigator became aware of profit possibilities in the trans-Saharan trade routes.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] For centuries slave and gold trade routes linking West Africa with the Mediterranean passed over the Western Sahara Desert, controlled by the Moors.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] He invested in sponsoring voyages down the coast of Mauritania, gathering merchants, shipowners and stakeholders interested in new sea lanes.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Soon the Atlantic islands of Madeira (1419) and the Azores (1427) were reached.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] The expedition leader who established settlements on Madeira, was explorer João Gonçalves Zarco.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Europeans did not know what lay beyond Cape Non (Cape Chaunar) on the African coast, and whether it was possible to return once crossed.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Nautical myths warned of monsters or an edge of the world, but Henry's navigation challenged such beliefs: starting in 1421, systematic sailing overcame it, reaching the difficult Cape Bojador that in 1434 one of Henry's captains, Gil Eanes, finally passed.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] From 1440, caravels were extensively used for the exploration of the coast of Africa.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] This was an Iberian ship type, used for fishing, commerce and military purposes.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] It had a sternpost-mounted rudder, a shallow draft helpful in exploring coastlines, a good sailing performance, with a windward ability.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] The lateen rig was less useful when sailing downwind – which explains Christopher Columbus (Italian: *Cristoforo Colombo*) re-rigging the *Niña* with square rig.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] For celestial navigation the Portuguese used the ephemerides, which experienced a remarkable diffusion in the 15th century.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] These were astronomical charts plotting the location of the stars.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Published in 1496 by Jewish astronomer and mathematician Abraham Zacuto, the Almanac Perpetuum included some of these tables for the movements of stars.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] These revolutionized navigation, allowing the calculation of latitude.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Exact longitude remained elusive from mariners for centuries.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Using the caravel, systematic exploration continued southerly, advancing one degree a year.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Senegal and Cape Verde Peninsula were reached in 1445 and in 1446, Álvaro Fernandes pushed on almost as far as present-day Sierra Leone.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1453, the fall of Constantinople to the Ottomans was a perceived blow to Christendom and established business links with the East.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] The king, who had been inquiring of Genoese experts about a seaway to India, commissioned the Fra Mauro world map, which arrived in Lisbon in 1459.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1456, Diogo Gomes reached the Cape Verde archipelago.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] In the next decade captains at the service of Prince Henry, discovered the remaining islands which were occupied during the 15th century.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] The Gulf of Guinea was reached in the 1460s.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1460, Pedro de Sintra reached Sierra Leone.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Prince Henry died in November after which, given the meagre revenues, exploration was granted to Lisbon merchant Fernão Gomes in 1469, who in exchange for the monopoly of trade in the Gulf of Guinea had to explore 100 miles (161 kilometres) each year for five years.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] With his sponsorship, explorers João de Santarém, Pedro Escobar, Lopo Gonçalves, Fernão do Pó, and Pedro de Sintra made it beyond those goals.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] They reached the Southern Hemisphere and islands of the Gulf of Guinea, including São Tomé and Príncipe and Elmina in 1471.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] There, in what came to be called the "Gold Coast", in today's Ghana, a thriving alluvial gold trade was found among the natives, Arab and Berber traders.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1478, during the War of the Castilian Succession, near the coast at Elmina a large battle was fought between a Castilian armada of 35 caravels, and a Portuguese fleet for the hegemony of the Guinea trade.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] The war ended with a Portuguese victory, followed by official recognition by the Catholic Monarchs of Portuguese sovereignty over most of the disputed West African territories embodied in the Treaty of Alcáçovas, 1479.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1481, João II decided to build São Jorge da Mina factory.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1482, the Congo River was explored by Diogo Cão, who in 1486 continued to Cape Cross (modern Namibia).
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] The next crucial breakthrough was in 1488, when Bartolomeu Dias rounded the southern tip of Africa, which he named Cabo das Tormentas, "Cape of Storms", then sailing east as far as the mouth of the Great Fish River, proving the Indian Ocean was accessible from the Atlantic.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Pero da Covilhã, sent out travelling secretly overland, had reached Ethiopia having collected important information about the Red Sea and Quenia coast, suggesting a sea route to the Indies would soon be forthcoming.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Soon the cape was renamed by King John II of Portugal the *Cape of Good Hope*, because of the optimism engendered by the possibility of a sea route to India, proving false the view that had existed since Ptolemy that the Indian Ocean was land-locked.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Based on later stories of the phantom island known as Bacalao and the carvings on Dighton Rock some have speculated that Portuguese explorer João Vaz Corte-Real discovered Newfoundland in 1473, but the sources are considered unreliable.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Portugal's Iberian rival, Castile, had begun to establish its rule over the Canary Islands in 1402, but became distracted by internal Iberian politics and the repelling of Islamic invasion attempts through most of the 15th century.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Following the unification of the crowns of Castile and Aragon, an emerging modern Spain became committed to the search for new trade routes overseas.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] The Crown of Aragon had been an important maritime power, controlling territories in eastern Spain, southwestern France, major islands like Sicily, Malta, and the Kingdom of Naples and Sardinia, with mainland possessions as far as Greece.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1485 and 1488, Columbus had presented the project to king John II of Portugal, who rejected it.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] On 3 August 1492, Columbus departed from Palos de la Frontera.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Land was sighted on 12 October, and Columbus called the island *San Salvador* (Guanahani now in The Bahamas), in what he thought to be the East Indies.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Columbus explored the north coast of Cuba and Hispaniola, by 5 December.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] He was received by the native cacique Guacanagari, who gave him permission to leave some men behind.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Columbus left 39 and founded the settlement of *La Navidad* in what is now Haiti.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Before returning to Spain, he kidnapped 10-25 natives.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Only 7-8 of the 'Indians' arrived alive, but they made an impression on Seville.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] On 15 March 1493, he arrived in Barcelona, where he reported to Isabella and Ferdinand.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Word of his discovery of new lands spread throughout Europe.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Columbus and other Spanish explorers were initially disappointed with their discoveries—unlike Africa or Asia, the Caribbean islanders had little to trade.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] The islands thus became the focus of colonization efforts.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] It was not until the continent was explored that Spain found the wealth it had sought.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Shortly after Columbus's return from what would be called the "West Indies", a division of influence became necessary to avoid conflict between the Spaniards and Portuguese.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] It did not mention Portugal, which could not claim newly discovered lands east of the line.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] King John II of Portugal was displeased with the arrangement, feeling it gave him too little land—preventing him from reaching India, his goal.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] He negotiated directly with Ferdinand and Isabella to move the line west, allowing him to claim newly discovered lands east of it.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1494, the Treaty of Tordesillas divided the world between Portugal and Spain.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Portugal gained control over Africa, Asia, and eastern South America (Brazil), encompassing everything outside Europe east of a line drawn 370 leagues west of the Cape Verde islands.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] The Spaniards received everything west of this line, including the islands discovered by Columbus on his first voyage.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] The dividing line, situated about halfway between Portuguese Cape Verde and Spanish discoveries in the Caribbean, split the known world of Atlantic islands evenly.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1500, Pedro Álvares Cabral, initially considering the Brazilian coast as a large island, claimed it for Portugal east of the dividing line.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] This claim was acknowledged by the Spaniards.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Cabral, heading towards India, followed a corridor in the Atlantic negotiated by the treaty for favorable winds.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Later the Spanish territory would prove to include huge areas of the continental mainland of North and South America, though Portuguese-controlled Brazil would expand across the line, and settlements by other European powers ignored the treaty.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Little of the divided area had actually been seen by Europeans, as it was only divided by a geographical definition rather than control on the ground.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] The desire to compete with the Ottoman Empire and Columbus's first voyage spurred further maritime exploration and, from 1497, other explorers headed west.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] That year John Cabot (Italian: *Giovanni Caboto*), also a commissioned Italian, got letters patent from King Henry VII of England.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Sailing from Bristol Cabot crossed the Atlantic from a northerly latitude hoping the voyage to the "West Indies" would be shorter and made landfall in North America, possibly Newfoundland.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Prior to Cabot's voyage, the furthest European expeditions in the North Atlantic had been by Norse explorers, who established settlements in Newfoundland and Greenland, which were abandoned in the 11th century and mid-15th century, respectively.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Merchants from Bristol had sponsored exploratory voyages in the 1480s, which did not report anything of note.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1499, João Fernandes Lavrador was licensed by the King of Portugal and together with Pero de Barcelos they first sighted Labrador, which was granted and named after him.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Between 1499 and 1502, the brothers Gaspar and Miguel Corte Real explored and named the coasts of Greenland and Newfoundland.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Both explorations are noted in the 1502 Cantino planisphere.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1497, newly crowned King Manuel I of Portugal sent an exploratory fleet eastwards, fulfilling his predecessor's project of finding a route to the Indies.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] In July 1499, news spread that the Portuguese had reached the "true Indies", as a letter was dispatched by the Portuguese king to the Spanish Monarchs.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] The third expedition by Columbus in 1498 was the beginning of the first successful Spanish colonization in the West Indies, on the island of Hispaniola.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Despite growing doubts, Columbus refused to accept he had not reached the Indies.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] He discovered the mouth of the Orinoco River on the north coast of South America and thought the huge quantity of fresh water coming from it could only be from a continental land mass, which he was certain was Asia.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] As shipping between Seville and the West Indies grew, knowledge of the Caribbean islands, Central America and the northern coast of South America increased.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] One of these Spanish fleets, that of Alonso de Ojeda and Amerigo Vespucci in 1499–1500 reached land at the coast of what is now Guyana, where the two seem to have separated in opposite directions.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Vespucci sailed southward, discovering the mouth of the Amazon River in July 1499, and reaching 6°S, in present-day north east Brazil, before turning around.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Vicente Yáñez Pinzon was blown off course and reached what is now the northeast coast of Brazil on 26 January 1500, exploring as far south as the present-day state of Pernambuco.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] His fleet was the first to fully enter the Amazon River estuary, which he named *Saint Mary's River of the Freshwater Sea*.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] The land was too far east for the Castilians to claim under the Treaty of Tordesillas, but the discovery created Castilian interest, with a second voyage by Pinzon in 1508 (the Pinzón–Solís voyage) and a voyage in 1515–1516 by a navigator of the 1508 expedition, Juan Díaz de Solís.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] The 1515–1516 expedition was spurred on by reports of Portuguese exploration of the region.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] It ended when de Solís and some of his crew disappeared when exploring the River Plata in a boat, but what they found reignited Spanish interest, and colonization began in 1531.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] In April 1500, the second Portuguese India Armada, headed by Pedro Álvares Cabral, with a crew of expert captains, encountered the Brazilian coast as it swung westward in the Atlantic while performing a large volta do mar to avoid becalming in the Gulf of Guinea.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] On 21 April, a mountain was seen and named *Monte Pascoal*, and on 22 April Cabral landed.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] On 25 April, the entire fleet sailed into the harbour they named *Porto Seguro*.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Cabral perceived that the new land lay east of the line of Tordesillas, and sent an envoy to Portugal with the discovery in letters, including the letter of Pero Vaz de Caminha.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Believing the land to be an island, he named it Ilha de Vera Cruz.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] From the east coast, the fleet then turned eastward towards the southern tip of Africa and India.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Cabral was the first captain to touch four continents, leading the first expedition that connected and united Europe, Africa, the New World, and Asia.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] At the invitation of King Manuel I of Portugal, Amerigo Vespucci participated as an observer in the exploratory voyages to the east coast of South America.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] It was understood that Columbus had not reached Asia but found a new continent, the Americas.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] The Americas were named in 1507 by cartographers Martin Waldseemüller and Matthias Ringmann, after Amerigo Vespucci.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] From 1501 to 1502, one of these Portuguese expeditions, led by Gonçalo Coelho, sailed south along the coast of South America to the bay of present-day Rio de Janeiro.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Vespucci's account states that the expedition reached the latitude "South Pole elevation 52° S", in the "cold" latitudes of what is now southern Patagonia, before turning back.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Vespucci wrote that they headed toward the southwest and south, following "a long, unbending coastline", apparently coincident with the southern South American coast.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] This seems controversial, since he changed part of his description in the subsequent letter, stating a shift, from about 32° S (Southern Brazil) to the south-southeast, to open sea, maintaining that they reached 50°/52° S.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1503, Binot Paulmier de Gonneville, challenging the Portuguese policy of *mare clausum*, led one of the earliest French Normand and Breton expeditions to Brazil.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] He intended to sail to the East Indies, but near the Cape of Good Hope, his ship was diverted to the west by a storm, and landed in the present-day state of Santa Catarina (southern Brazil), on 5 January 1504.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] From 1511 to 1512, Portuguese captains João de Lisboa and Estevão de Fróis reached the River Plata estuary in present-day Uruguay and Argentina, and went as far south as the present-day Gulf of San Matias at 42°S.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] The expedition reached a cape extending north to south which they called Cape of "Santa Maria" (Punta del Este); and after 40°S they found a "Cape" or "a point or place extending into the sea", and a "Gulf".
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] After they had navigated for nearly 300 km (186 mi) to round the cape, they again sighted the continent on the other side and steered towards the northwest, but a storm prevented them from making headway.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Driven away by the *Tramontane* or north wind, they retraced their course.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] Christopher de Haro, a Fleming of Sephardic origin, who would serve the Spanish Crown after 1516, believed the navigators had discovered a southern *strait* to west and Asia.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1519, an expedition sent by the Spanish Crown to find a way to Asia was led by the experienced Portuguese navigator Ferdinand Magellan.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] The fleet explored the rivers and bays as it charted the South American coast, until it found a way to the Pacific Ocean through the Strait of Magellan.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] From 1524 to 1525, Aleixo Garcia, a Portuguese conquistador, led a private expedition of shipwrecked Castilian and Portuguese adventurers, who recruited about 2,000 Guaraní Indians.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] They explored the territories of present-day southern Brazil, Paraguay, and Bolivia, using the native trail network, the *Peabiru*.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p01] They were the first Europeans to cross the Chaco and reach the outer territories of the Inca Empire on the hills of the Andes.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Protected from direct Spanish competition by the Treaty of Tordesillas, Portuguese eastward exploration and colonization continued apace.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Twice, in 1485 and 1488, Portugal officially rejected Genoese Christopher Columbus's idea of reaching India by sailing westwards.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] King John II of Portugal's experts rejected it, for they held the opinion that Columbus's estimation of a travel distance of 2,400 miles (3,860 km) was low, and in part because Bartolomeu Dias departed in 1487 trying the rounding of the southern tip of Africa.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] They believed that sailing east would require a far shorter journey.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Dias's return from the Cape of Good Hope in 1488, and Pero da Covilhã's travel to Ethiopia overland indicated that the richness of the Indian Ocean was accessible from the Atlantic.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] In July 1497, a small exploratory fleet of four ships and about 170 men left Lisbon under the command of Vasco da Gama.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] By December the fleet passed the Great Fish River—where Dias had turned back—and sailed into waters unknown to the Europeans.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Sailing into the Indian Ocean, da Gama entered a maritime region that had three different and well-developed trade circuits.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] The one da Gama encountered connected Mogadishu on the east coast of Africa; Aden, at the tip of the Arabian peninsula; the Persian port of Hormuz; Cambay, in northwestern India; and Calicut, in southwestern India.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] On 20 May 1498, they arrived at Calicut.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] The efforts of Vasco da Gama to get favorable trading conditions were hampered by the low value of their goods, compared with the valuable goods traded there.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Two years and two days after departure, Gama and a survivor crew of 55 men returned in glory to Portugal as the first ships to sail directly from Europe to India.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Da Gama's voyage is romanticized in the Os Lusíadas, an epic poem by fellow discovery-era traveler Luís de Camões.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] The poem is widely regarded as Portugal's greatest literary achievement.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1500, a second, larger fleet of thirteen ships and about 1500 men were sent to India.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Under the command of Pedro Álvares Cabral, they made the first landfall on the Brazilian coast, giving Portugal its claim.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Later, in the Indian Ocean, one of Cabral's ships reached Madagascar (1501), which was partly explored by Tristão da Cunha in 1507; Mauritius was discovered in 1507, Socotra occupied in 1506.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] In the same year Lourenço de Almeida landed in Sri Lanka, the eastern island named "Taprobane" in remote accounts of Alexander the Great's and 4th-century BC Greek geographer Megasthenes.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] On the Asiatic mainland, the first factories (trading-posts) were established at Kochi and Calicut (1501) and then Goa (1510).
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] The Portuguese continued sailing eastward from India, entering a second existing circuit of the Indian Ocean trade, from Calicut and Quillon in India, to Southeast Asia, including Malacca and Palembang.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1511, Afonso de Albuquerque conquered Malacca for Portugal, then the center of Asian trade.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] East of Malacca, Albuquerque sent several diplomatic missions: Duarte Fernandes as the first European envoy to the Kingdom of Siam (modern Thailand).
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Learning the location of the so-called "spice islands", heretofore a secret from the Europeans, were the Spice Islands, mainly the Banda, then the world's only source of nutmeg and cloves.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Reaching these was the main purpose for the Portuguese voyages in the Indian Ocean.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Albuquerque sent an expedition led by António de Abreu to Banda (via Java and the Lesser Sunda Islands), where they were the first Europeans to arrive in early 1512, after taking a route through which they also reached first the islands of Buru, Ambon, and Seram.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] In May 1513, Jorge Álvares, one of the Portuguese envoys, reached China.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Fernão Pires de Andrade visited Canton in 1517 and opened up trade with China.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] After a few decades, hostilities between the Portuguese and Chinese ceased and in 1557 the Chinese allowed the Portuguese to occupy Macau.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] To enforce a trade monopoly, Muscat and Hormuz in the Persian Gulf were seized by Afonso de Albuquerque in 1507 and in 1515, respectively.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] He also entered into diplomatic relations with Persia.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1513, while trying to conquer Aden, an expedition led by Albuquerque cruised the Red Sea inside the Bab al-Mandab and sheltered at Kamaran island.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1521, a force under António Correia conquered Bahrain, ushering in a period of almost 80 years of Portuguese rule of the Gulf archipelago.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] In the Red Sea, Massawa was the most northerly point frequented by the Portuguese until 1541, when a fleet under Estevão da Gama penetrated as far as Suez.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1513, about 40 miles (64 kilometres) south of Acandí, in present-day Colombia, Spanish Vasco Núñez de Balboa heard unexpected news of an "other sea" rich in gold, which he received with great interest.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] With few resources and using information given by *caciques*, he journeyed across the Isthmus of Panama with 190 Spaniards, a few native guides, and a pack of dogs.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Balboa, using a brigantine and ten native canoe, explored the coast, facing battles and dense jungles.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] On 25 September, after crossing the Chucunaque River mountains, he became the first European to see the Pacific Ocean from the New World.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] The expedition briefly navigated the Pacific, naming the bay *San Miguel* and the sea *Mar del Sur* (South Sea).
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Seeking gold, Balboa traversed cacique lands to the islands, naming the largest Isla Rica (now Isla del Rey) and the group *Archipiélago de las Perlas*, names still in use today.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] From 1515 to 1516, the Spanish fleet led by Juan Díaz de Solís sailed down the east coast of South America as far as Río de la Plata, which Solís named shortly before he died while trying to find a passage to the "South Sea".
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] By 1516, several Portuguese navigators conflicting with King Manuel I of Portugal gathered in Seville to serve the newly crowned Charles I of Spain.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Among them were explorers Diogo and Duarte Barbosa, Estêvão Gomes, João Serrão, and Ferdinand Magellan, cartographers Jorge Reinel and Diogo Ribeiro, cosmographers Francisco and Ruy Faleiro and the Flemish merchant Christopher de Haro.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Ferdinand Magellan had sailed in India for Portugal up to 1513, when the Spice Islands were reached, and had kept contact with Francisco Serrão who was living there.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Magellan developed the theory that the Spice Islands were in the Tordesillas Spanish area, based on studies by Faleiro brothers.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Aware of the efforts of the Spanish to find a route to India by sailing west, Magellan presented his plan to Charles I of Spain.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] The king and Christopher de Haro financed Magellan's expedition.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] A fleet was put together, and Spanish navigators such as Juan Sebastián Elcano joined the enterprise.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] On 10 August 1519, they departed from Seville with a fleet of five ships—the caravel flagship *Trinidad* under Magellan's command, and carracks *San Antonio*, *Concepcion*, *Santiago* and *Victoria*.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] They contained a crew of about 237 European men from several regions, with the goal of reaching the Spice Islands by travelling west, trying to reclaim it under Spain's economic and political sphere.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] The fleet sailed south, avoiding Portuguese Brazil, and became the first to reach Tierra del Fuego.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Starting on 21 October, they navigated the 373-mile (600 km) Strait of Magellan, entering the Pacific on 28 November, which Magellan named Mar Pacífico for its calm waters.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] After crossing the Pacific, Magellan was killed in the Battle of Mactan in the Philippines.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Juan Sebastián Elcano completed the voyage, reaching the Spice Islands in 1521.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] On 6 September 1522, the *Victoria* returned to Spain, completing the first circumnavigation of the globe.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Of the original crew, only 18 men completed the circumnavigation; 17 returned later, including twelve captured by the Portuguese and five survivors of the Trinidad.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Antonio Pigafetta, a Venetian scholar, kept a detailed journal that is a key source of information about the voyage.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] This round-the-world voyage gave Spain valuable knowledge of the world and its oceans which later helped in the exploration and settlement of the Philippines.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Soon after Magellan's expedition, the Portuguese rushed to seize the surviving crew and built a fort in Ternate.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1525, Charles I of Spain sent another expedition westward to colonize the Spice Islands, claiming that they were in his zone of the Treaty of Tordesillas.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] The fleet of seven ships and 450 men was led by García Jofre de Loaísa and included the most notable Spanish navigators: Juan Sebastián Elcano and Loaísa, who died then, and the young Andrés de Urdaneta.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Near the Strait of Magellan one of the ships was pushed south by a storm, reaching 56° S, where they thought seeing "*earth's end*": so Cape Horn was crossed for the first time.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] The expedition reached the islands with great difficulty, docking at Tidore.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] The conflict with the Portuguese established in nearby Ternate was inevitable, starting nearly a decade of skirmishes.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] As there was not a set eastern limit to the Tordesillas line, both kingdoms organized meetings to resolve the issue.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] From 1524 to 1529, Portuguese and Spanish experts met at Badajoz-Elvas trying to find the exact location of the antimeridian of Tordesillas, which would divide the world into two equal hemispheres.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Each crown appointed three astronomers and cartographers, three pilots, and three mathematicians.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Lopo Homem, Portuguese cartographer and cosmographer was on the board, along with cartographer Diogo Ribeiro of the Spanish delegation.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] The board met several times without reaching an agreement: the knowledge at that time was insufficient for an accurate calculation of longitude, and each group gave the islands to its sovereign.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] The issue was settled only in 1529, after a long negotiation, with the signing of Treaty of Zaragoza, which allocated the Spice Islands to Portugal and the Philippines to Spain.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] From 1525 to 1528, Portugal sent several expeditions around the Spice Islands.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Gomes de Sequeira and Diogo da Rocha were sent north by the governor of Ternate Jorge de Menezes, being the first Europeans to reach the Caroline Islands, which they named *Islands of Gomes de Sequeira*.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1526, Jorge de Meneses docked on Biak and Waigeo islands, Papua New Guinea.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Based on these explorations stands the theory of Portuguese discovery of Australia, one among several competing theories about the early discovery of Australia, supported by Australian historian Kenneth McIntyre, stating it was discovered by Cristóvão de Mendonça and Gomes de Sequeira.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1527, Hernán Cortés fitted out a fleet to find new lands in the "South Sea" (Pacific Ocean), asking his cousin Álvaro de Saavedra Cerón to take charge.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] On 31 October 1527, Saavedra sailed from New Spain, crossing the Pacific and touring the north of New Guinea, then named *Isla de Oro*.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] In October 1528, one of the vessels reached the Spice Islands.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] In his attempt to return to New Spain he was diverted by the northeast trade winds, which threw him back, so he tried sailing back down, to the south.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] He returned to New Guinea and sailed northeast, where he sighted the Marshall Islands and the Admiralty Islands, but again was surprised by the winds, which brought him a third time to the Moluccas.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] This westbound return route was hard to find but was eventually discovered by Andrés de Urdaneta in 1565.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Rumors of undiscovered islands northwest of Hispaniola reached Spain by 1511, ushering King Ferdinand's interest in forestalling further exploration.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] While the Portuguese were making huge gains in the Indian Ocean, the Spanish invested in exploring inland in search of gold and other valuable resources.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] The members of these expeditions, the conquistadors, were not soldiers in an army, but more like soldiers of fortune; they came from a variety of backgrounds including artisans, merchants, clergy, lawyers, lesser nobility and a few freed slaves.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] They usually supplied their own equipment or were extended credit to purchase it in exchange for a share in profits.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] They usually had no professional military training, but a number of them had previous experience on other expeditions.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] In the Americas, the Spanish encountered large indigenous empires and formed alliances with indigenous people through small expeditions.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] After establishing Spanish sovereignty and discovering wealth, the crown focused on implementing Spanish state and church institutions.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] A key element was the 'spiritual conquest' through Christian evangelization.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] The initial economy relied on a tribute and forced labor under the *encomienda* system.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] The discovery of vast silver deposits transformed both the colonial economies of Mexico and Peru and Spain's economy.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] With global trade networks and valuable American crops, Spain's economy strengthened, enhancing its status as a world power.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] During this time, pandemics of European diseases such as smallpox decimated the indigenous populations.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1512, to reward Juan Ponce de León for exploring Puerto Rico in 1508, King Ferdinand urged him to seek these new lands.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] He would become governor of discovered lands but was to finance himself all exploration.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] With three ships and about 200 men, Léon set out from Puerto Rico in March 1513.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] In April, they sighted land and named it *La Florida*—because it was Easter (Florida) season—believing it was an island, becoming credited as the first European to land in the continent.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] The arrival location has been disputed between St.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Augustine, Ponce de León Inlet and Melbourne Beach.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] They headed south for further exploration and on 8 April encountered a current so strong that it pushed them backward: this was the first encounter with the Gulf Stream that would soon become the primary route for eastbound ships leaving the Spanish Indies bound for Europe.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] They explored down the coast reaching Biscayne Bay, Dry Tortugas and then sailing southwest in an attempt to circle Cuba to return, reaching Grand Bahama on July.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1517, Cuba's governor Diego Velázquez de Cuéllar commissioned a fleet under the command of Hernández de Córdoba to explore the Yucatán Peninsula.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] They reached the coast where Mayans invited them to land.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] They were attacked at night and only a remnant of the crew returned.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Velázquez then commissioned another expedition led by his nephew Juan de Grijalva, who sailed south along the coast to Tabasco, part of the Aztec Empire.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1518, Velázquez gave the mayor of the capital of Cuba, Hernán Cortés, the command of an expedition to secure the interior of Mexico but, due to an old gripe between them, revoked the charter.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] In February 1519, Cortés went ahead anyway, in an act of open mutiny.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] With about 11 ships, 500 men, 13 horses, and a small number of cannons he landed in Yucatán, in Mayan territory, claiming the land for the Spanish crown.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] From Trinidad he proceeded to Tabasco and won a battle against the natives.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Among the vanquished was Marina (La Malinche), his future mistress, who knew both (Aztec) Nahuatl language and Maya, becoming a valuable interpreter and counsellor.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] In July, his men took over Veracruz and he placed himself under direct orders of new king Charles I of Spain.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] There Cortés asked for a meeting with Aztec emperor Moctezuma II, who repeatedly refused.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] They headed to Tenochtitlan and on the way made alliances with several tribes.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] In October, accompanied by about 3,000 Tlaxcaltec they marched to Cholula, the second largest city in central Mexico.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Either to instill fear upon the Aztecs waiting for him or (as he later claimed) wishing to make an example when he feared native treachery, they massacred thousands of unarmed members of the nobility gathered at the central plaza and partially burned the city.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] On 8 November, Cortés and his large army were welcomed by Moctezuma II in Tenochtitlan, who hoped to learn about them to eventually defeat them.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Moctezuma gave lavish gifts, which led Cortés to plunder the city.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Cortés claimed the Aztecs saw him as an emissary or incarnation of the god Quetzalcōātl, though this is contested by few historians.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Upon learning that his men had been attacked on the coast, Cortés took Moctezuma hostage in his palace, demanding tribute for King Charles.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Meanwhile, Velasquez sent another expedition, led by Pánfilo de Narváez, to oppose Cortès, arriving in Mexico in April 1520 with 1,100 men.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Cortés left 200 men in Tenochtitlan and took the rest to confront Narvaez, whom he overcame, convincing his men to join him.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] In Tenochtitlán, one of Cortés's lieutenants committed a massacre in the Great Temple, triggering local rebellion.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Cortés speedily returned, attempting the support of Moctezuma but the Aztec emperor was killed, possibly stoned by his subjects.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] The Spaniards fled for Tlaxcala during the *Noche Triste*, where they managed a narrow escape while their back guard was massacred.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Much of the treasure looted was lost during this panicked escape.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] After a battle in Otumba they reached Tlaxcala, having lost 870 men.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Having prevailed with the assistance of allies and reinforcements from Cuba, Cortés besieged Tenochtitlán and captured its ruler Cuauhtémoc in August 1521.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] As the Aztec Empire ended, he claimed the city for Spain and renamed it Mexico City.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] A first attempt to explore western South America was undertaken in 1522 by Pascual de Andagoya.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Native South Americans told him about a gold-rich territory on a river called Pirú.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Having reached San Juan River (Colombia), Andagoya fell ill and returned to Panama, where he spread the news about "Pirú" as the legendary El Dorado.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] These, along with the accounts of the success of Hernán Cortés, caught the attention of Pizarro.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Francisco Pizarro had accompanied Balboa in the crossing of the Isthmus of Panama.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1524, he formed a partnership with priest Hernando de Luque and soldier Diego de Almagro to explore the south, agreeing to divide the profits.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] They dubbed the enterprise the "*Empresa del Levante*": Pizarro would command, Almagro would provide military and food supplies, and Luque would be in charge of finances and additional provisions.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] On 13 September 1524, the first of three expeditions set out to conquer Peru with 80 men and 40 horses.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] The venture failed, halting in Colombia due to bad weather, hunger, and conflicts with locals; Almagro lost an eye.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Their route was marked by *Puerto Deseado* (desired port), *Puerto del Hambre* (port of hunger), and *Puerto quemado* (burned port).
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Two years later, a second expedition began with reluctant permission from the Governor of Panama.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] In August 1526, they departed with two ships, 160 men, and horses.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Upon reaching the San Juan River, Pizarro explored swampy coasts, while Almagro sought reinforcements.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Pizarro's pilot, sailing south and crossing the equator, captured a raft from Tumbes.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] To his surprise, the raft carried coveted textiles, ceramics, gold, silver, and emeralds, becoming the expedition's main focus.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Almagro later joined with reinforcements, and despite challenging conditions, they reached Atacames, where a sizable native population under Inca rule was observed, though they did not land.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Pizarro, safe near the coast, sent Almagro and Luque for reinforcements with proof of the rumoured gold.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] The new governor rejected a third expedition, ordering everyone back to Panama.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Almagro and Luque seized the chance to rejoin Pizarro.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] At *Isla de Gallo*, Pizarro drew a line, presenting the choice between Peru's riches and Panama's poverty.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Thirteen men, The Famous Thirteen, stayed and headed to *La Isla Gorgona*, staying seven months until provisions arrived.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] They sailed south and by April 1528, reached northwestern Peru's Tumbes region, warmly received by the *Tumpis*.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Pizarro's men reported incredible riches, llama sightings, and the natives named them "Children of the Sun" for their fair complexion and brilliant armour.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] They decided to return to Panama to prepare a final expedition, sailing south through named territories like Cabo Blanco, port of Payta, Sechura, Punta de Aguja, Santa Cruz, and Trujillo, reaching the ninth degree south.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] In the spring of 1528, Pizarro sailed for Spain, where he had an interview with king Charles I.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] The king heard of his expeditions in lands rich in gold and silver and promised to support him.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] The *Capitulación de Toledo* authorized Pizarro to proceed with the conquest of Peru.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Pizarro was then able to convince many friends and relatives to join: his brothers Hernándo Pizarro, Juan Pizarro, Gonzalo Pizarro, and also Francisco de Orellana, who would later explore the Amazon River, as well as his cousin Pedro Pizarro.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Pizarro's third and final expedition left Panama for Peru on 27 December 1530.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] With three ships and one hundred and eighty men, they landed near Ecuador and sailed to Tumbes, finding the place destroyed.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] They entered the interior and established the first Spanish settlement in Peru, San Miguel de Piura.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] One of the men returned with an Incan envoy and an invitation for a meeting.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Since the last meeting, the Inca had begun a civil war and Atahualpa had been resting in northern Peru following the defeat of his brother Huáscar.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] After marching for two months, they approached Atahualpa.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] He refused the Spanish, saying he would be "no man's tributary".
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] There were fewer than 200 Spanish to his 80,000 soldiers, but Pizarro attacked and won against the Incan army in the Battle of Cajamarca, taking Atahualpa captive at the so-called Ransom Room.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Despite fulfilling his promise of filling one room with gold and two with silver, he was convicted for killing his brother and plotting against Pizarro, and was executed.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] After the Spanish had sealed the conquest of Peru, Jauja in fertile Mantaro Valley was established as Peru's provisional capital, but it was too far up in the mountains, and Pizarro founded the city of Lima on 18 January 1535, which Pizarro considered one of the most important acts in his life.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1543, three Portuguese traders accidentally became the first Westerners to reach and trade with Japan.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] According to Fernão Mendes Pinto, who claimed to be in this journey, they arrived at Tanegashima, where the locals were impressed by firearms that would be immediately made by the Japanese on a large scale.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] The Spanish conquest of the Philippines was ordered by Philip II of Spain, and Andrés de Urdaneta was the designated commander.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Urdaneta agreed to accompany the expedition but refused to command and Miguel López de Legazpi was appointed instead.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] The expedition set sail in November 1564.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] After spending some time on the islands, Legazpi sent Urdaneta back to find a better return route.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Urdaneta set sail from San Miguel on the island of Cebu on 1 June 1565, but was obliged to sail as far as 38 degrees North latitude to obtain favorable winds.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] He reasoned that the trade winds of the Pacific might move in a gyre as the Atlantic winds did.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] If in the Atlantic, ships made the *Volta do mar* to pick up winds that would bring them back from Madeira, then, he reasoned, by sailing far to the north before heading east, he would pick up trade winds to bring him back to North America.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] His hunch paid off, and he hit the coast near Cape Mendocino, California, then followed the coast south.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] The ship reached the port of Acapulco, on 8 October 1565, having traveled 12,000 miles (19,000 kilometres) in 130 days.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Fourteen of his crew died; only Urdaneta and Felipe de Salcedo, nephew of López de Legazpi, had strength enough to cast the anchors.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Thus, a cross-Pacific Spanish route was established, between Mexico and the Philippines.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] For a long time, these routes were used by the Manila galleons, thereby creating a trade link joining China, the Americas, and Europe via the combined trans-Pacific and trans-Atlantic routes.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] European nations outside Iberia did not recognize the Treaty of Tordesillas between Portugal and Castile, nor did they recognize Pope Alexander VI's donation of the Spanish finds in the New World.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] France, the Netherlands, and England each had a long maritime tradition and had been engaging in privateering.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Despite Iberian protections, the new technologies and maps soon made their way north.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] After the marriage of Henry VIII of England and Catherine of Aragon failed to produce a male heir and Henry failed to obtain a papal dispensation to annul his marriage, he broke with the Roman Catholic Church and established himself as head of the Church of England.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] This added religious conflict to political conflict.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] When much of The Netherlands became Protestant, it sought political and religious independence from Catholic Spain.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1568, the Dutch rebelled against the rule of Philip II of Spain leading to the Eighty Years' War.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] The war between England and Spain also broke out.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1580, Philip II became King of Portugal, as heir to its Crown.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Although he ruled Portugal and its empire as separate from the Spanish Empire, the union of the crowns produced a Catholic superpower, which England and the Netherlands challenged.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] In the eighty-year Dutch War of Independence, Philip's troops conquered the important trading cities of Bruges and Ghent.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Antwerp, then the most important port in the world, fell in 1585.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] The Protestant population was given two years to settle affairs before leaving the city.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Those were mainly skilled craftsmen, rich merchants of the port cities and refugees that fled religious persecution, particularly Sephardic Jews from Portugal and Spain and, later, the Huguenots from France.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] The Pilgrim Fathers also spent time there before going to the New World.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] This mass immigration was an important driving force: a small port in 1585, Amsterdam quickly transformed into one of the most important commercial centres in the world.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] After the failure of the Spanish Armada in 1588, there was a huge expansion of maritime trade even though the defeat of the English Armada would confirm the naval supremacy of the Spanish navy over the emergent competitors.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Dutch maritime power rose quickly as Dutch sailors, skilled in navigation and mapmaking, engaged with Portuguese voyages.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1592, Cornelis de Houtman gathered information on the Spice Islands in Lisbon.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] The same year, Jan Huyghen van Linschoten published a detailed travel report in Amsterdam, providing navigation instructions for reaching the East Indies and Japan.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Following this, Houtman led the Dutch's first exploratory voyage, discovering a new route from Madagascar to the Sunda Strait and securing a treaty with the Banten Sultan.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] The Dutch also demonstrated their maritime strength by seizing Malacca from Portugal in 1641, following a series of battles that began in 1602.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Dutch and British interest, fed on new information, led to a movement of commercial expansion, and the foundation of English (1600) and Dutch (1602) chartered companies.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Dutch, French, and English sent ships which flouted the Portuguese monopoly, concentrated mostly on the coastal areas, which proved unable to defend against such a vast and dispersed venture.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] The 1497 English expedition authorized by Henry VII of England was led by Italian Venetian John Cabot (Giovanni Caboto); it was the first of a series of French and English missions exploring North America.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Mariners from the Italian peninsula played an important role in early explorations, most especially Genoese mariner Christopher Columbus.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] With its major conquests of central Mexico and Peru and discoveries of silver, Spain put limited efforts into exploring the northern part of the Americas; its resources were concentrated in Central and South America where more wealth had been found.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] These other European expeditions were initially motivated by the same idea as Columbus, namely a westerly shortcut to the Asian mainland.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] After the existence of "another ocean" (the Pacific) was confirmed by Balboa in 1513, there still remained the motivation of potentially finding an oceanic Northwest Passage for Asian trade.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] This was not discovered until the early twentieth century, but other possibilities were found, although nothing on the scale of the spectacular ones of the Spanish.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] In the early 17th century colonists from a number of Northern European states began to settle on the east coast of North America.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1524, Italian Giovanni da Verrazzano sailed under the authority of Francis I of France, who was motivated by indignation over the division of the world between Portuguese and Spanish.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Verrazzano explored the Atlantic Coast of North America, from South Carolina to Newfoundland, and was the first recorded European to visit what would later become the Virginia Colony and the United States.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] In the same year Estêvão Gomes, a Portuguese cartographer who had sailed in Ferdinand Magellan's fleet, explored Nova Scotia, sailing South through Maine, where he entered what is now New York Harbor, the Hudson River and eventually reached Florida in August 1525.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] As a result of his expedition, the 1529 Diogo Ribeiro world map outlines the East coast of North America almost perfectly.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Europeans explored the Pacific Coast beginning in the mid-16th century.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Spaniard Francisco de Ulloa explored the Pacific coast of present-day Mexico including the Gulf of California, proving that Baja California was a peninsula.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Despite his report based on first-hand information, the myth persisted in Europe that California was an island.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] His account provided the first recorded use of the name "California".
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] João Rodrigues Cabrilho, a Portuguese navigator sailing for the Spanish Crown, was the first European to set foot in California, landing on 28 September 1542, on the shores of San Diego Bay and claiming California for Spain.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] He also landed on San Miguel, one of the Channel Islands, and continued as far north as Point Reyes on the mainland.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] After his death, the crew continued exploring as far north as Oregon.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] The English privateer Francis Drake sailed along the coast in 1579 north of Cabrillo's landing site while circumnavigating the world.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Drake had a long and largely successful career attacking Spanish settlements in the Caribbean islands and the mainland so for the English, he was a great hero and fervent Protestant, but for the Spanish, he was "a frightening monster".
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Drake played a major role in the defeat of the Spanish Armada in 1588 but led an armada himself to the Spanish Caribbean that was unsuccessful in dislodging the Spanish.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] On 5 June 1579, the ship briefly made first landfall at South Cove, Cape Arago, just south of Coos Bay, Oregon, and then sailed south while searching for a suitable harbor to repair his damaged ship.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] On 17 June, Drake and his crew found a protected cove when they landed on the Pacific coast of what is now Northern California near Point Reyes.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] While ashore, he claimed the area for Queen Elizabeth I of England as Nova Albion or New Albion.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] To document and assert his claim, Drake posted an engraved plate of brass to claim sovereignty for Queen Elizabeth and her successors on the throne.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Drake's landfalls on the west coast of North America are one small part of his 1577–1580 circumnavigation of the globe, the first captain of his own ship to do so.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Drake died in 1596 off the coast of Panama, following injuries from a raid.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] He explored the Hudson River and laid the foundation for Dutch colonization of the region.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Hudson's final expedition ranged farther north in search of the Northwest Passage, leading to his discovery of the Hudson Strait and Hudson Bay.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] After wintering in James Bay, Hudson tried to press on with his voyage in the spring of 1611, but his crew mutinied and they cast him adrift.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] France, the Netherlands, and England sought a sea route to Asia after finding none through Africa or South America.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] With no route through the Americas, they focused on northern passages, driving European exploration of the Arctic coasts.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] The idea of a link between the Atlantic and Pacific was first proposed by Russian diplomat Gerasimov in 1525, though Russian Pomors had explored parts of the route as early as the 11th century.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1553, English explorer Hugh Willoughby with chief pilot Richard Chancellor were sent out with three vessels in search of a passage by London's Company of Merchant Adventurers to New Lands.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] During the voyage across the Barents Sea, Willoughby thought he saw islands to the north, and islands called Willoughby's Land were shown on maps published by Plancius and Mercator into the 1640s.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] The vessels were separated by "terrible whirlwinds" in the Norwegian Sea and Willoughby sailed into a bay near the present border between Finland and Russia.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] His ships with the frozen crews, including Captain Willoughby and his journal, were found by Russian fishermen a year later.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Richard Chancellor was able to drop anchor in the White Sea and make his way overland to Moscow and Ivan the Terrible's court, opening trade with Russia and the Company of Merchant Adventurers became the Muscovy Company.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] In June 1576, English mariner Martin Frobisher led an expedition consisting of three ships and 35 men to search for a north-west passage around North America.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] The voyage was supported by the Muscovy Company, the same merchants that hired Hugh Willoughby to find a northeast passage above Russia.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Violent storms sank one ship and forced another to turn back but Frobisher and the remaining ship reached the coast of Labrador in July.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] A few days later they came upon the mouth of what is now Frobisher Bay.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Frobisher believed it to be the entrance to a north-west passage and named it Frobisher's Strait and claimed Baffin Island for Queen Elizabeth.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] After some preliminary exploration, Frobisher returned to England.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] He commanded two subsequent voyages in 1577 and 1578 but failed to find the hoped-for passage.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Frobisher brought to England his ships laden with ore, but it was found to be worthless and damaged his reputation as an explorer.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] He remains an important early historical figure in Canada.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] On 5 June 1594, Dutch cartographer Willem Barentsz departed from Texel in a fleet of three ships to enter the Kara Sea, with the hopes of finding the Northeast Passage above Siberia.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] At Williams Island the crew encountered a polar bear for the first time.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] They managed to bring it on board, but the bear rampaged and was killed.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Barentsz reached the west coast of Novaya Zemlya and followed it northward, before being forced to turn back in the face of large icebergs.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] The following year, Prince Maurice of Orange named him chief pilot of a new expedition of six ships, loaded with merchant wares that the Dutch hoped to trade with China.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] The party came across Samoyed "wild men" but eventually turned back upon discovering the Kara Sea frozen.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1596, the States-General offered a high reward for anybody who *successfully* navigated the Northeast Passage.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] The Town Council of Amsterdam purchased and outfitted two small ships, captained by Jan Rijp and Jacob van Heemskerck, to search for the elusive channel, under the command of Barents.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] They set off in May, and in June discovered Bear Island and Spitsbergen, sighting its northwest coast.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] They saw a large bay, later called Raudfjorden and entered Magdalenefjorden, which they named *Tusk Bay*, sailing into the northern entrance of Forlandsundet, which they called *Keerwyck*, but were forced to turn back because of a shoal.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] On 28 June they rounded the northern point of Prins Karls Forland, which they named *Vogelhoek*, on account of a large number of birds, and sailed south, passing Isfjorden and Bellsund, which were labelled on Barentsz's chart as *Grooten Inwyck* and *Inwyck*.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] The ships once again reached Bear Island on 1 July, which led to a disagreement.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] They parted ways, with Barentsz continuing northeast, while Rijp headed north.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Barentsz reached Novaya Zemlya and, to avoid becoming entrapped in ice, headed for the Kara Strait but became stuck within the icebergs and floes.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Stranded, the 16-man crew was forced to spend the winter on the ice.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] The crew used lumber from their ship to build a lodge they called *Het Behouden Huys* (The Kept House).
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Dealing with extreme cold, they used merchant fabrics to make additional blankets and clothing and caught Arctic foxes in primitive traps, as well as polar bears.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] When June arrived, and the ice had still not loosened its grip on the ship, scurvy-ridden survivors took two small boats out into the sea.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Barentsz died at sea on 20 June 1597, while studying charts.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] It took seven more weeks for the boats to reach Kola where they were rescued by a Russian merchant vessel.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Only 12 crewmen remained, reaching Amsterdam in November.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Two of Barentsz' crewmembers later published their journals, Jan Huyghen van Linschoten, who had accompanied him on the first two voyages, and Gerrit de Veer who had acted as the ship's carpenter on the last.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Juan Fernández, sailing from Chile in 1576, claimed he had discovered the Southern Continent.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Luís Vaz de Torres, a Galician navigator working for the Spanish Crown, proved the existence of a passage south of New Guinea, now known as Torres Strait.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Pedro Fernandes de Queirós, a Portuguese navigator sailing for the Spanish Crown, saw a large island south of New Guinea in 1606, which he named *Austrialia del Espiritu Santo* (transl.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Southern-Austrian Land of the Holy Spirit).
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] He represented this to the King of Spain as the *Terra Australis incognita*, but it was present-day Vanuatu rather than Australia or Antarctica.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Dutch navigator and colonial governor, Willem Janszoon sailed from the Netherlands for the East Indies for the third time on 18 December 1603, as captain of *Duyfken* (or *Duijfken*, meaning 'Little Dove'), one of twelve ships of the great fleet of Steven van der Hagen.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Once in the Indies, Janszoon was sent to search for other outlets of trade, particularly in "the great land of Nova Guinea and other East and Southlands".
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] On 18 November 1605, *Duyfken* sailed from Banten to the coast of western New Guinea.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Janszoon then crossed the eastern end of the Arafura Sea, without becoming aware of the Torres Strait, into the Gulf of Carpentaria.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] On 26 February 1606, he made landfall at the Pennefather River on the western shore of Cape York in Queensland, near the modern town of Weipa.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] This is the first recorded European landfall on the Australian continent.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Janszoon proceeded to chart some 320 kilometres (199 mi) of the coastline, which he thought was a southerly extension of New Guinea.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1615, Jacob Le Maire and Willem Schouten's rounding of Cape Horn proved that Tierra del Fuego was a relatively small island.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] From 1642 to 1644, Abel Tasman, also a Dutch explorer and merchant in the service of the VOC, circumnavigated New Holland proving that Australia was not part of the mythical southern continent.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] He was the first known European expedition to reach the islands of Van Diemen's Land (now Tasmania) and New Zealand and to sight the Fiji islands, which he did in 1643.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p02] Tasman, his navigator Visscher, and his merchant Gilsemans also mapped substantial portions of Australia, New Zealand, and the Pacific islands.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] In the mid-16th century, the Tsardom of Russia conquered the Tatar khanates of Kazan and Astrakhan, thus annexing the entire Volga region and opening the way to the Ural Mountains.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] The colonization of the new easternmost lands of Russia and further onslaught eastward was led by the rich merchants Stroganovs.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] Ivan the Terrible granted vast estates near the Urals as well as tax privileges to Anikey Stroganov, who organized large-scale migration to these lands.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] The Stroganovs developed farming, hunting, saltworks, fishing, and ore mining on the Urals and established trade with Siberian tribes.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] Around 1577, Semyon Stroganov and other sons of Anikey Stroganov hired a Cossack leader called Yermak to protect their lands from the attacks of Khan Kuchum.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] By 1580, Stroganovs and Yermak came up with the idea of a military expedition to Siberia, to fight Kuchum in his own land.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1581, Yermak began his voyage into the depths of Siberia.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] After a few victories over the Khan's army, Yermak's people defeated the main forces of Kuchum on Irtysh River in the three-day Battle of Chuvash Cape in 1582.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] The remains of the Khan's army retreated to the steppes, and thus Yermak captured the Khanate of Sibir, including its capital Qashliq near modern Tobolsk.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] Kuchum still was strong and suddenly attacked Yermak in 1585 in the dead of night, killing most of his people.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] Yermak was wounded and tried to swim across the Wagay River (Irtysh's tributary), but drowned under the weight of his own chain mail.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] The Cossacks had to withdraw from Siberia completely, but thanks to Yermak's having explored all the main river routes in West Siberia, Russians successfully reclaimed all his conquests just several years later.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] In the early 17th century, the eastward movement of Russians was slowed by the internal problems in the country during the Time of Troubles.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] Very soon, exploration and colonization of the huge territories of Siberia resumed, led mostly by Cossacks hunting for valuable furs and ivory.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] While Cossacks came from the Southern Urals, another wave of Russians came by the Arctic Ocean.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] These were Pomors from the Russian North, who already had been making fur trade with Mangazeya in the north of Western Siberia for quite a long time.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1607, the settlement of Turukhansk was founded on the northern Yenisey River, near the mouth of Lower Tunguska.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1619, Yeniseysk ostrog was founded on the mid-Yenisey at the mouth of the Upper Tunguska.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] Between 1620 and 1624, a group of fur hunters led by Demid Pyanda left Turukhansk and explored some 1,430 miles (2,300 kilometres) of the Lower Tunguska, wintering in the proximity of the Vilyuy and Lena Rivers.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] According to later legendary accounts (folktales collected a century after the fact), Pyanda discovered the Lena.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] He allegedly explored some 1,500 miles (2,400 kilometres) of its length, reaching as far as central Yakutia.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] He returned up the Lena until it became too rocky and shallow, and portaged to the Angara River.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] In this way, Pyanda may have become the first Russian to meet Yakuts and Buryats.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] He built new boats and explored some 870 miles (1,400 kilometres) of the Angara, finally reaching Yeniseysk and discovering that the Angara (a Buryat name) and Upper Tunguska (Verkhnyaya Tunguska, as initially known by Russians) are one and the same river.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1627, Pyotr Beketov was appointed Yenisei voevoda in Siberia.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] He successfully carried out the voyage to collect taxes from the Zabaykalye Buryats, becoming the first Russian to step in Buryatia.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] He founded the first Russian settlement there, Rybinsky ostrog.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] Beketov was sent to the Lena River in 1631, where in 1632 he founded Yakutsk and sent his Cossacks to explore the Aldan River and farther down the Lena, to found new fortresses, and to collect taxes.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] Yakutsk soon turned into a major starting point for further Russian expeditions eastward, southward and northward.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] Maksim Perfilyev, who earlier had been one of the founders of Yeniseysk, founded Bratsk ostrog on the Angara in 1631.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1638, Perfilyev became the first Russian to step into Transbaikalia, travelling there from Yakutsk.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1643, Kurbat Ivanov led a group of Cossacks from Yakutsk to the south of the Baikal Mountains and discovered Lake Baikal, visiting its Olkhon Island.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] Ivanov later made the first chart and description of Baikal.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1639, a group of explorers led by Ivan Moskvitin became the first Russians to reach the Pacific Ocean and to discover the Sea of Okhotsk, having built a winter camp on its shore at the Ulya River mouth.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] The Cossacks learned from the locals about the large Amur River far to the south.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1640, they apparently sailed south, and explored the south-eastern shores of the Okhotsk Sea, perhaps reaching the mouth of the Amur River and possibly discovering the Shantar Islands on their way back.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] Based on Moskvitin's account, Kurbat Ivanov drew the first Russian map of the Far East in 1642.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1643, Vassili Poyarkov crossed the Stanovoy Range and reached the upper Zeya River in the country of the Daurs, who were paying tribute to the Manchus.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] After wintering, in 1644, Poyarkov pushed down the Zeya and became the first Russian to reach the Amur River.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] He sailed down the Amur and finally discovered the mouth of that great river from land.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] Since his Cossacks provoked the enmity of the locals behind, Poyarkov chose a different way back.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] They built boats and in 1645, sailed along the Sea of Okhotsk coast to the Ulya River and spent the next winter in the huts that had been built by Ivan Moskvitin six years earlier.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1644, Mikhail Stadukhin discovered the Kolyma River and founded Srednekolymsk.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] A merchant named Fedot Alekseyevich Popov organized a further expedition eastward, and Semyon Dezhnyov became a captain of one of the kochi.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1648, they sailed from Srednekolymsk down to the Arctic and after some time they rounded Cape Dezhnyov, thus becoming the first explorers to pass through the Bering Strait and discover Chukotka and the Bering Sea.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] All their Kochi and most of their men (including Popov himself) were lost in storms and clashes with the natives.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] A small group led by Dezhnyov reached the mouth of the Anadyr River and sailed up it in 1649, having built new boats from the wreckage.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] They founded Anadyrsk and were stranded there until Stadukhin found them, coming from Kolyma by land.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] Subsequently, Stadukhin set off south in 1651 and discovered Penzhin Bay on the northern coast of the Okhotsk Sea.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] He also may have explored the western shores of Kamchatka.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] From 1649 to 1650, Yerofey Khabarov became the second Russian to explore the Amur River.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] Through the Olyokma, Tungir, and Shilka Rivers he reached Amur (Dauriya), returned to Yakutsk and then back to Amur with a larger force in 1650–1653.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] This time he was met with armed resistance.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] He built winter quarters at Albazin, then sailed down Amur and found Achansk, which preceded the present-day Khabarovsk, defeating or evading large armies of Daurs, Manchus, Chinese, and Koreans on his way.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] He charted the Amur in his *Draft of the Amur river*.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] Subsequently, the Russians held on to the Amur region until 1689, when by the Treaty of Nerchinsk this land was assigned to the Qing Empire.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] It was returned by the Treaty of Aigun in 1858.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] From 1659 to 1665, Kurbat Ivanov was the next head of Anadyrsky ostrog after Semyon Dezhnev.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1660, he sailed from Anadyr Bay to Cape Dezhnyov.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] By the mid-17th century, the Russians established the borders of their country close to modern ones, and explored almost the whole of Siberia, except the eastern Kamchatka and some regions north of the Arctic Circle.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] The conquest of Kamchatka later would be achieved in the early 1700s by Vladimir Atlasov, while the discovery of the Arctic coastline and Alaska would be completed by the Great Northern Expedition in 1733–1743.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] European overseas expansion led to contact between the Old and New Worlds producing the Columbian exchange.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] It started the global silver trade between the Americas, Europe, and China, and led to direct European involvement in the Chinese porcelain trade.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] It involved the transfer of goods unique from one hemisphere to another.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] From the Old World, Europeans brought cattle, horses, and sheep to the New World, and from the New World Europeans received tobacco, potatoes, tomatoes, and maize.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] Other items and commodities becoming important in global trade were the tobacco, sugarcane, and cotton crops of the Americas, along with the gold and silver brought from the American continent not only to Europe, but elsewhere in the Old World.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] The formation of new transoceanic links and expansion of European influence led to the Age of Imperialism, which began during the Age of Discovery, during which colonial powers from Europe colonized most territory on the planet.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] Combined with the introduction of infectious diseases from Europe, these events led to a drastic decrease of the American Indian population.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] American Indian accounts of European colonization were summarized by scholar Peter Mancall: "The arrival of Europeans brought death, displacement, sorrow, and despair to Native Americans".
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] In some areas, like North America, Central America, Australia, New Zealand, and Argentina, indigenous peoples were poorly treated, driven off their lands, and reduced to dependent minorities in the territory.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] Similarly, in East and West Africa, local states supplied the appetite of European slave traders, changing the complexion of coastal African states and fundamentally altering the nature of slavery in Africa, causing impacts on societies and economies deep inland.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] In North America, there were many conflicts between European colonists and American Indians.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] Maize and manioc were introduced into Africa in the 16th century by the Portuguese.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] They are now important staple foods, replacing native African crops.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] Crosby speculated that increased production of maize, manioc, and other New World crops led to heavier concentrations of population in the areas from which slavers captured their victims.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] In the global silver trade, China was stimulated by trade with the Portuguese, Spaniards, and Dutch.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] Although global, much of that silver ended up with the Chinese, and China dominated silver imports.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] Between 1600 and 1800, China received 100 tons of silver on average per year.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] A large populace near the Lower Yangtze averaged hundreds of taels of silver per household in the late 16th century.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] More than 150,000 tons of silver were shipped from Potosí by the end of the 18th century.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] From 1500 to 1800, Mexico and Peru produced about 80% of the world's silver, with more than 30% of it eventually ending up in China (largely because European merchants used it to purchase exotic Chinese commodities).
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] In the late 16th and early 17th century, Japan was exporting heavily into China and foreign trade at large.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] Trade with European powers and the Japanese brought in significant amounts of silver, which then replaced copper and paper banknotes as the common medium of exchange in China.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] During the last decades of the Ming dynasty, the flow of silver into China was greatly diminished, thereby undermining state revenues and the entire Ming economy.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] This damage to the economy was compounded by the effects on agriculture of the incipient Little Ice Age, natural calamities, crop failure, and sudden epidemics.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] The ensuing breakdown of authority and people's livelihoods allowed rebel leaders such as Li Zicheng to challenge Ming authority.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] New crops that had come to Asia from the Americas, via the Spanish colonizers in the 16th century, contributed to Asia's population growth.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] Although the bulk of imports to China were silver, the Chinese also purchased New World crops from the Spanish Empire.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] This included sweet potatoes, maize, and peanuts, foods that could be cultivated in lands where traditional Chinese staple crops—wheat, millet, and rice—could not grow, hence facilitating a rise in the population of China.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] In the Song dynasty (960–1279), rice had become the major staple crop of the poor; after sweet potatoes were introduced to China around 1560, it gradually became the traditional food of the lower classes.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] The arrival of the Portuguese to Japan in 1543 initiated the Nanban trade period, with the Japanese adopting technologies and cultural practices, like the arquebus, European-style cuirasses, European ships, Christianity, decorative art, and language.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] After the Chinese had banned direct trade by Chinese merchants with Japan, the Portuguese filled this commercial vacuum as intermediaries.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] The Portuguese bought Chinese silk and sold it to the Japanese in return for Japanese-mined silver; since silver was more highly valued in China, the Portuguese could then use Japanese silver to buy even larger stocks of Chinese silk.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] By 1573, after the Spaniards established a trading base in Manila, the Portuguese intermediary trade was trumped by the prime source of incoming silver to China from the Spanish Americas.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] Although China acted as the cog running the wheel of global trade during the 16th to 18th centuries, Japan's huge contribution of silver exports to China was critical to the world economy and China's liquidity and success with the commodity.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] As a wider variety of global luxury commodities entered the European markets by sea, previous European markets for luxury goods stagnated.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] The Atlantic trade largely supplanted pre-existing Italian and German trading powers which had relied on their Baltic, Russian, and Islamic trade links.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] The new commodities also caused social change, as sugar, spices, silks, and chinawares entered the luxury markets of Europe.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] The European economic centre shifted from the Mediterranean to Western Europe.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] The city of Antwerp, part of the Duchy of Brabant, became "the centre of the *entire* international economy", and the richest city in Europe.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] Centred in Antwerp first and then Amsterdam, the Dutch Golden Age was tightly linked to the Age of Discovery.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] By 1549, the Portuguese empire sent annual trade missions to Shangchuan Island in China.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1557, they managed to convince the Ming court to agree on a legal port treaty that would establish Macau as an official Portuguese trade colony.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] From China, the major exports were silk and porcelain, adapted to meet European tastes.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] The Chinese export porcelains were held in such great esteem in Europe that, in English, *china* became a commonly used synonym for *porcelain*.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] Kraak porcelain was among the first Chinese ware to arrive in Europe in significant quantities; only the richest could afford these early imports.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] Soon the Dutch East India Company established trade with the East, having imported 6 million porcelain items from China to Europe between 1602 and 1682.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] Kraak, mainly the blue and white porcelain, was imitated all over the world by potters in Arita, Japan and Persia—where Dutch merchants turned when the fall of the Ming dynasty rendered Chinese originals unavailable—and ultimately in delftware.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] Dutch and later English delftware inspired by Chinese designs persisted from about 1630 to the mid-18th century alongside European patterns.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] Antonio de Morga (1559–1636), a Spanish official in Manila, listed an extensive inventory of goods that were traded by Ming China at the turn of the 16th to 17th century, noting there were "rarities which, did I refer to them all, I would never finish, nor have sufficient paper for it".
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] Ebrey writes of the considerable size of commercial transactions: In one case a galleon to the Spanish territories in the New World carried over 50,000 pairs of silk stockings.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] In return China imported mostly silver from Peruvian and Mexican mines, transported via Manila.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] Chinese merchants were active in these trading ventures, and many emigrated to such places as the Philippines and Borneo to take advantage of the new commercial opportunities.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] The increase in gold and silver experienced by Spain coincided with a major inflationary cycle within Spain and Europe, known as the price revolution.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] Spain had amassed large quantities of gold and silver from the New World.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] In the 1540s, large scale extraction of silver from Mexico began.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] During the 16th century, Spain held the equivalent of US$1.5 trillion (1990 terms) in gold and silver from New Spain.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] Being the most powerful European monarch at a time full of war and religious conflicts, the Habsburg rulers spent their wealth in wars and arts across Europe.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] The spent silver, spread throughout a cash-starved Europe, caused widespread inflation.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] The inflation was worsened by a growing population with a static production level, low salaries and a rising cost of living, which damaged local industry.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] Increasingly, Spain became dependent on the revenues flowing in from the mercantile empire, leading to Spain's first bankruptcy in 1557 due to rising military costs.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] Philip II of Spain defaulted on debt payments in 1557, 1560, 1575, and 1596.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] The increase in prices as a result of currency circulation fuelled the growth of the commercial middle class in Europe, the *bourgeoisie*, which came to influence the politics and culture of many countries.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] One effect of the inflation, particularly in Great Britain, was that tenant farmers who held long-term leases from lords saw real decreases in rent.
[src:brig/age-of-discovery-p03] Some lords opted to sell their leased land, giving rise to small, landowning farmers.
[src:brig/age-of-sail] The **Age of Sail** is the period in European history from the mid-15th or 16th century to, at the latest, the mid-19th century, in which the dominance of sailing ships in global trade and warfare culminated.
[src:brig/age-of-sail] Marked by the introduction of naval artillery, the Age of Sail ultimately reached its highest extent at the advent of steam power.
[src:brig/age-of-sail] Enabled by the advances of the related age of navigation, it is identified as a distinctive element of the early modern period and the Age of Discovery.
[src:brig/age-of-sail] Like most periodic eras, defining the age is inexact and serves only as a general description.
[src:brig/age-of-sail] The term is used differently for warships and merchant vessels.
[src:brig/age-of-sail] By the 14th century naval artillery was employed in Europe, documented at the Battle of Arnemuiden (1338).
[src:brig/age-of-sail] The 15th century saw the Iberian naval ventures all the way along the African Atlantic coast and across the Atlantic Ocean, starting the Age of Discovery.
[src:brig/age-of-sail] For warships, the age of sail runs roughly from the Battle of Lepanto in 1571, the last significant engagement in which oar-propelled galleys played a major role, to the development of steam-powered warships.
[src:brig/age-of-sail] The period between the mid-19th century to the early 20th century, when sailing vessels reached their peak of size and complexity (e.g. clippers and windjammers), is sometimes referred to as the "Golden Age of Sail".
[src:brig/age-of-sail] The second sea-going steamboat was Richard Wright's first steamboat *Experiment*, an ex-French lugger; she steamed from Leeds to Yarmouth in July 1813.
[src:brig/age-of-sail] The first iron steamship to go to sea was the 116-ton *Aaron Manby*, built in 1821 by Aaron Manby at the Horseley Ironworks, and became the first iron-built vessel to put to sea when she crossed the English Channel in 1822, arriving in Paris on 22 June.
[src:brig/age-of-sail] She carried passengers and freight to Paris in 1822 at an average speed of 8 knots (9.2 mph; 15 km/h).
[src:brig/age-of-sail] The first purpose-built steam battleship was the 90-gun *Napoléon* in 1850.
[src:brig/age-of-sail] Multiple steam battleships saw action during the Crimean War, especially the Allied (British, French and Ottoman) fleet Bombardment of Sevastopol as part of the Siege of Sevastopol (1854–1855).
[src:brig/age-of-sail] The first ironclad battleship, *Gloire*, was launched by the French Navy in November 1859.
[src:brig/age-of-sail] In the March 1862 Battle of Hampton Roads, the ironclad CSS *Virginia* fought USS *Monitor*, making this the first fight between ironclads.
[src:brig/age-of-sail] The Suez Canal in the Middle East, which opened in 1869, was more practical for steamships than for sailing ships, achieving a much shorter European-Asian sea route, which coincided with more fuel-efficient steamships, starting with *Agamemnon* in 1865.
[src:brig/age-of-sail] HMS *Devastation*, the first class of ocean-going battleships that did not carry sails, was commissioned in 1871.
[src:brig/age-of-sail] Sailing ships continued to be an economical way to transport bulk cargo on long voyages into the 1920s and 1930s, though steamships soon pushed them out of those trades as well.
[src:brig/age-of-sail] Sailing ships do not require fuel or complex engines to be powered; thus they tended to be more independent from sophisticated dedicated support bases on land.
[src:brig/age-of-sail] Crucially though, steam-powered ships held a speed advantage and were rarely hindered by adverse winds, freeing steam-powered vessels from the necessity of following trade winds.
[src:brig/age-of-sail] As a result, cargo and supplies could reach a foreign port in a fraction of the time it took a sailing ship.
[src:brig/age-of-sail] Sailing vessels were pushed into narrower and narrower economic niches and gradually disappeared from commercial trade.
[src:brig/age-of-sail] Today, sailing vessels are only economically viable for small-scale coastal fishing, along with recreational uses such as yachting and passenger sail excursion ships.
[src:brig/age-of-sail] In recent decades, the commercial shipping industry has been reviving interest in wind assisted ships as a way to conserve fuel in the interest of sustainability.
[src:brig/age-of-sail] A **New Age of Sail** has been predicted by some experts to occur by 2030, driven by a revolution in energy technology and a desire to reduce carbon emissions from maritime shipping through wind-assisted propulsion.
[src:brig/age-of-sail] The book *Trade Winds: A Voyage to a Sustainable Future for Shipping* discusses the potential of a return to wind propulsion through the firsthand experiences of Christiaan De Beukelaer, who spent five months aboard a sailing cargo ship in 2020.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] An **aircraft carrier** is a warship designed to carry, launch, recover and support aircraft at sea, equipped with a full-length flight deck and hangar facilities that allow it to serve as a mobile, seagoing airbase.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] Typically it is the capital ship of a fleet (known as a carrier battle group), as it allows a naval force to project seaborne air power far from national territory without depending on local airfields for the staging of aircraft operations.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] While heavier fixed-wing aircraft such as airlifters, gunships and bombers have been launched from aircraft carriers, these aircraft do not often land on a carrier due to flight deck limitations.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] The aircraft carrier, along with its onboard aircraft and defensive ancillary weapons, is the largest weapon system ever created.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] By their tactical prowess, mobility, autonomy and the variety of operational means, aircraft carriers are often the centerpiece of modern naval warfare, and have significant diplomatic influence in deterrence, command of the sea and air supremacy.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] Since the Second World War, the aircraft carrier has replaced the battleship in the role of flagship of a fleet, and largely transformed naval battles from gunfire to beyond-visual-range air strikes.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] Modern navies use several variants of the aircraft carrier, sometimes categorized as sub-types of aircraft carriers and sometimes as distinct types of aviation-capable ships.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] Aircraft carriers may be classified according to the type of aircraft they carry and their operational assignments.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] Navies have a variety of classification systems for their ships, and a definitive number of current aircraft carriers depends on the specific criteria.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] As of July 2026 there are 9 navies operating 24 active vessels designated by their respective navies as either an "Aircraft Carrier" or "Aircraft Cruiser".
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] These range in tonnage from the United States' 100,000 tonne USS *Gerald R.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] Ford* to Brazil's 21,000 tonne NAM *Atlantico*.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] Some of the types listed here are not strictly defined as aircraft carriers by some sources.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] A fleet carrier is intended to operate with the main fleet and usually provides an offensive capability.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] These are the largest carriers capable of fast speeds.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] By comparison, escort carriers were developed to provide defense for convoys of ships.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] They were smaller and slower with lower numbers of aircraft carried.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] Most were built from mercantile hulls or, in the case of merchant aircraft carriers, were bulk cargo ships with a flight deck added on top.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] Light aircraft carriers were fast enough to operate with the main fleet but of smaller size with reduced aircraft capacity.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] The Soviet aircraft carrier *Admiral Kusnetsov* was termed a "heavy aircraft-carrying cruiser".
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] This was primarily a legal construct to avoid the limitations of the Montreux Convention preventing 'aircraft carriers' transiting the Turkish Straits between the Soviet Black Sea bases and the Mediterranean Sea.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] These ships, while sized in the range of large fleet carriers, were designed to deploy alone or with escorts.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] In addition to supporting fighter aircraft and helicopters, they provide both strong defensive weaponry and heavy offensive missiles equivalent to a guided-missile cruiser.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] The appellation "supercarrier" is not an official designation with any national navy, but a term used predominantly by the media and typically when reporting on larger and more advanced carrier types.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] It is also used when comparing carriers of various sizes and capabilities, both current and past.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] It was first used by *The New York Times* in 1938, in an article about the Royal Navy's HMS *Ark Royal*, that had a length of 800 feet (244 m), a displacement of 22,000 tons and was designed to carry 72 aircraft.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] Since then, aircraft carriers have consistently grown in size, both in length and displacement, as well as improved capabilities; in defense, sensors, electronic warfare, propulsion, range, launch and recovery systems, number and types of aircraft carried and number of sorties flown per day.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] The first aircraft carrier over 80,000 tonnes full-load displacement was the USS Forrestal launched in 1954.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] In total, the US Navy has had 5 different classes of aircraft carrier of this size definition, the Forrestal class, Kitty Hawk class, the Enterprise class, the Nimitz class and Gerald R Ford Class, two of which were conventional steam-powered and three nuclear-powered.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] USS *Enterprise*, launched in 1960, was the first carrier over 90,000 tonnes full load displacement and *Nimitz*, launched in 1972, was the first over 100,000 tonnes displacement.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] A total of 22 supercarriers have been launched by the US Navy since 1954, with 11 currently in service.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] Both China (Type 003) and the United Kingdom (Queen Elizabeth class) have carriers in service with displacements from 80,000 to 85,000 tonnes and lengths from 280 to 320 meters (920 to 1,050 ft) which are described as "supercarriers".
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] France is also developing a new aircraft carrier (PANG) which is to have a full load displacement of 80,000 tonnes and will be considered a supercarrier.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] The largest supercarrier in service as of 2024 is the US Navy's USS Gerald R.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] Ford, with full load displacement of around 100,000 tons, length of 337 meters (1,106 ft) and capabilities that exceed those of any other class.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] A US Navy proposal for an aircraft carrier concept with a length of 1,310 feet and a displacement of 500,000 tons full load at a cost of $828 million in 1976 dollars.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] Project Habakkuk could be considered an early proposal for an "ultracarrier".
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] Several systems of identification symbol for aircraft carriers and related types of ship have been used.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] These include the pennant numbers used by the Royal Navy, Commonwealth countries, and Europe, along with the hull classification symbols used by the US and Canada.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] Two months later, on 18 January 1911, Ely landed his Curtiss Pusher airplane on a platform on the armored cruiser USS *Pennsylvania* anchored in San Francisco Bay.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] Seaplane tender support ships came next, with the French *Foudre* of 1911.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] Early in World War I, the Imperial Japanese Navy ship *Wakamiya* conducted the world's first carrier-launched air raid: on 6 September 1914, the *Wakamiya* used its crane to lower Farman seaplanes into the water.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] The *Wakamiya* attacked the Austro-Hungarian cruiser SMS *Kaiserin Elisabeth* and the Imperial German gunboat *Jaguar* in Jiaozhou Bay off Qingdao; neither was hit.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] The first attack using an air-launched torpedo occurred on 2 August, when a torpedo was fired by Flight Commander Charles Edmonds from a Short Type 184 seaplane, launched from the seaplane carrier HMS *Ben-my-Chree*.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] The first carrier-launched airstrike was the Tondern raid in July 1918.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] Seven Sopwith Camels were launched from the battlecruiser HMS *Furious*, which had been completed as a carrier by replacing her planned forward turret with a flight deck and hangar prior to commissioning.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] The Camels attacked and damaged the German airbase at Tondern, Germany (modern day Tønder, Denmark), and destroyed two zeppelin airships.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] The first landing of an airplane on a moving ship was by Squadron Commander Edwin Harris Dunning, when he landed his Sopwith Pup on HMS *Furious* in Scapa Flow, Orkney, on 2 August 1917.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] Landing on the forward flight deck required the pilot to approach round the ship's superstructure, a difficult and dangerous manoeuver, and Dunning was later killed when his airplane was thrown overboard while attempting another landing on *Furious*.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] HMS *Furious* was modified again when her rear turret was removed and another flight deck added over a second hangar for landing aircraft over the stern.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] Her funnel and superstructure remained intact, however, and turbulence from the funnel and superstructure was severe enough that only three landing attempts were successful before further attempts were forbidden.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] This experience prompted the development of vessels with a flush deck and produced the first large fleet ships.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] In 1918, HMS *Argus* became the world's first carrier capable of launching and recovering naval aircraft.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] As a result of the Washington Naval Treaty of 1922, which limited the construction of new heavy surface combat ships, most early aircraft carriers were conversions of ships that were laid down (or had served) as different ship types: cargo ships, cruisers, battlecruisers, or battleships.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] These conversions gave rise to the USS *Langley* in 1922, the US *Lexington*-class aircraft carriers (1927), Japanese *Akagi* and *Kaga*, and British *Courageous* class (of which *Furious* was one).
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] Specialist carrier evolution was well underway, with several navies ordering and building warships that were purposefully designed to function as aircraft carriers by the mid-1920s.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] This resulted in the commissioning of ships such as the Japanese *Hōshō* (1922), HMS *Hermes* (1924, although laid down in 1918 before *Hōshō*), and *Béarn* (1927).
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] During World War II, these ships would become known as fleet carriers.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] The aircraft carrier dramatically changed naval warfare in World War II, because air power was becoming a significant factor in warfare.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] The advent of aircraft as focal weapons was driven by the superior range, flexibility, and effectiveness of carrier-launched aircraft.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] They had greater range and precision than naval guns, making them highly effective.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] The versatility of the carrier was demonstrated in November 1940, when HMS *Illustrious* launched a long-range strike on the Italian fleet at their base in Taranto, signalling the beginning of the effective and highly mobile aircraft strikes.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] This operation in the shallow water harbor incapacitated three of the six anchored battleships at a cost of two torpedo bombers.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] World War II in the Pacific Ocean involved clashes between aircraft carrier fleets.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] The Japanese surprise attack on the American Pacific fleet at Pearl Harbor naval and air bases on Sunday, 7 December 1941, was a clear illustration of the power projection capability afforded by a large force of modern carriers.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] Concentrating six carriers in a single unit turned naval history about, as no other nation had fielded anything comparable.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] In the "Doolittle Raid", on 18 April 1942, the US Navy carrier USS *Hornet* sailed to within 650 nautical miles (1,200 km) of Japan and launched 16 B-25 Mitchell medium bombers from her deck in a demonstrative retaliatory strike on the mainland, including the capital, Tokyo.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] However, the vulnerability of carriers compared to traditional capital ships was illustrated by the sinking of HMS *Glorious* by German battleships during the Norwegian campaign in 1940.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] This new-found importance of naval aviation forced nations to create a number of carriers, in efforts to provide air superiority cover for every major fleet to ward off enemy aircraft.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] This extensive usage led to the development and construction of 'light' carriers.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] Escort aircraft carriers, such as USS *Bogue*, were sometimes purpose-built but most were converted from merchant ships as a stop-gap measure to provide anti-submarine air support for convoys and amphibious invasions.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] Following this concept, light aircraft carriers built by the US, such as USS *Independence* (commissioned in 1943), represented a larger, more "militarized" version of the escort carrier.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] Although with similar complement to escort carriers, they had the advantage of speed from their converted cruiser hulls.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] The UK 1942 Design Light Fleet Carrier was designed for building quickly by civilian shipyards and with an expected service life of about 3 years.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] They served the Royal Navy during the war, and the hull design was chosen for nearly all aircraft carrier equipped navies after the war, until the 1980s.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] Emergencies also spurred the creation or conversion of highly unconventional aircraft carriers.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] CAM ships were cargo-carrying merchant ships that could launch (but not retrieve) a single fighter aircraft from a catapult to defend the convoy from long range land-based German aircraft.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] Noteworthy converted carriers were also USS *Sable* (IX-81) and USS *Wolverine* (IX-64) that both operated on the Great Lakes for training duties and were converted from paddle steamers, making them the only aircraft carriers with this type of propulsion.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] Before World War II, international naval treaties of 1922, 1930, and 1936 limited the size of capital ships, including carriers.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] Since World War II, aircraft carrier designs have increased in size to accommodate a steady increase in aircraft size.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] The large, modern *Nimitz* class of US Navy carriers has a displacement nearly four times that of the World War II–era USS *Enterprise*, yet its complement of aircraft is roughly the same—a consequence of the steadily increasing size and weight of individual military aircraft over the years.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] Today's aircraft carriers are so expensive that some nations which operate them risk significant economic and military impact if a carrier is lost.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] Modern navies that operate such aircraft carriers treat them as capital ships of fleets, a role previously held by the galleons, ships-of-the-line and battleships.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] This change took place during World War II in response to air power becoming a significant factor in warfare, driven by the superior range, flexibility and effectiveness of carrier-launched aircraft.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] Following the war, carrier operations continued to increase in size and importance, and along with, carrier designs also increased in size and ability.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] Some of these larger carriers, dubbed by the media as "supercarriers", displacing 75,000 tons or greater, have become the pinnacle of carrier development.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] Some are powered by nuclear reactors and form the core of a fleet designed to operate far from home.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] Amphibious assault ships, such as the *Wasp* and *Mistral* classes, serve the purpose of carrying and landing Marines, and operate a large contingent of helicopters for that purpose.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] Also known as "commando carriers" or "helicopter carriers", many have the capability to operate VSTOL aircraft.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] The threatening role of aircraft carriers has a place in modern asymmetric warfare, like the gunboat diplomacy of the past.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] Carriers also facilitate quick and precise projections of overwhelming military power into such local and regional conflicts.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] Lacking the firepower of other warships, carriers by themselves are considered vulnerable to attack by other ships, aircraft, submarines, or missiles.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] The resulting group of ships is often termed a carrier strike group, battle group, carrier group, or carrier battle group.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] There is a view among some military pundits that modern anti-ship weapons systems, such as torpedoes and missiles, or even ballistic missiles with nuclear warheads have made aircraft carriers and carrier groups too vulnerable for modern combat.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] Carriers are large and long ships, although there is a high degree of variation depending on their intended role and aircraft complement.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] The size of the carrier has varied over history and among navies, to cater to the various roles that global climates have demanded from naval aviation.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] Regardless of size, the ship itself must house their complement of aircraft, with space for launching, storing, and maintaining them.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] Space is also required for the large crew, supplies (food, munitions, fuel, engineering parts), and propulsion.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] US and French aircraft carriers are notable for having nuclear reactors powering their systems and propulsion.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] The top of the carrier is the flight deck, where aircraft are launched and recovered.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] On the starboard side of this is the island, where ship navigation from the bridge and air traffic control from flyco are controlled and (in non-nuclear powered vessels), provides the location of the ship's funnel(s).
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] The *Queen Elizabeth*-class has two island structures; the forward island contains the navigation bridge, while the aft structure houses flyco.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] The constraints of constructing a flight deck strongly affect the role of a given carrier, as they influence the weight, type, and configuration of the aircraft that may be launched.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] For example, assisted launch mechanisms are used primarily for heavy aircraft, especially those loaded with air-to-ground weapons.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] CATOBAR is most commonly used on US Navy fleet carriers as it allows the deployment of heavy jets with full load-outs, especially on ground-attack missions.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] STOVL is used by other navies because it is cheaper to operate and still provides good deployment capability for fighter aircraft.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] Due to the busy nature of the flight deck, only 20 or so aircraft may be on it at any one time.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] A hangar storage several decks below the flight deck is where most aircraft are kept, and aircraft are taken from the lower storage decks to the flight deck through the use of an elevator.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] The hangar is usually quite large and can take up several decks of vertical space.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] Munitions are commonly stored on the lower decks because they are highly explosive.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] Usually this is below the waterline so that the area can be flooded in case of emergency.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] As "runways at sea", aircraft carriers have a flat-top flight deck, which launches and recovers aircraft.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] Aircraft launch forward, into the wind, and are recovered from astern.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] Creating such a surface at sea poses constraints on the carrier.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] For example, the size of the vessel is a fundamental limitation on runway length.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] This affects take-off procedure, as a shorter runway length of the deck requires that aircraft accelerate more quickly to gain lift.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] This either requires a thrust boost, a vertical component to its velocity, or a reduced take-off load (to lower mass).
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] The differing types of deck configuration, as above, influence the structure of the flight deck.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] The form of launch assistance a carrier provides is strongly related to the types of aircraft embarked and the design of the carrier itself.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] There are two main philosophies to keep the deck short: add thrust to the aircraft, such as using a Catapult Assisted Take-Off (CATO-); and changing the direction of the airplanes' thrust, as in Vertical and/or Short Take-Off (V/STO-).
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] On the recovery side of the flight deck, the adaptation to the aircraft load-out is mirrored.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] Non-VTOL or conventional aircraft cannot decelerate on their own, and almost all carriers using them must have arrested-recovery systems (-BAR, e.g.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] CATOBAR or STOBAR) to recover their aircraft.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] Aircraft that are landing extend a tailhook that catches on arrestor wires stretched across the deck to bring themselves to a stop in a short distance.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] If the aircraft are VTOL-capable or helicopters, they do not need to decelerate and hence there is no such need.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] The arrested-recovery system has used an angled deck since the 1950s because, in case the aircraft does not catch the arresting wire, the short deck allows easier take off by reducing the number of objects between the aircraft and the end of the runway.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] It also has the advantage of separating the recovery operation area from the launch area.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] Helicopters and aircraft capable of vertical or short take-off and landing (V/STOL) usually recover by coming abreast of the carrier on the port side and then using their hover capability to move over the flight deck and land vertically without the need for arresting gear.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] Carriers steam at speed, up to 35 knots (65 km/h; 40 mph) into the wind during flight deck operations to increase wind speed over the deck to a safe minimum.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] This increase in effective wind speed provides a higher launch airspeed for aircraft at the end of the catapult stroke or ski-jump, as well as making recovery safer by reducing the difference between the relative speeds of the aircraft and ship.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] Since the early 1950s on conventional carriers it has been the practice to recover aircraft at an angle to port of the axial line of the ship.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] The primary function of this angled deck is to allow aircraft that miss the arresting wires, referred to as a bolter, to become airborne again without the risk of hitting aircraft parked forward.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] The angled deck allows the installation of one or two "waist" catapults in addition to the two bow cats.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] An angled deck also improves launch and recovery cycle flexibility with the option of simultaneous launching and recovery of aircraft.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] Conventional ("tailhook") aircraft rely upon a landing signal officer (LSO, radio call sign 'paddles') to monitor the aircraft's approach, visually gauge glideslope, attitude, and airspeed, and transmit that data to the pilot.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] Before the angled deck emerged in the 1950s, LSOs used colored paddles to signal corrections to the pilot (hence the nickname).
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] From the late 1950s onward, visual landing aids such as the optical landing system have provided information on proper glide slope, but LSOs still transmit voice calls to approaching pilots by radio.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] Key personnel involved in the flight deck include the shooters, the handler, and the air boss.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] Shooters are naval aviators or naval flight officers and are responsible for launching aircraft.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] The handler works just inside the island from the flight deck and is responsible for the movement of aircraft before launching and after recovery.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] The captain of the ship spends most of his time one level below primary on the Navigation Bridge.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] Below this is the Flag Bridge, designated for the embarked admiral and his staff.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] To facilitate working on the flight deck of a US aircraft carrier, the sailors wear colored shirts that designate their responsibilities.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] There are at least seven different colors worn by flight deck personnel for modern United States Navy carrier air operations.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] Carrier operations of other nations use similar color schemes.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] The superstructure of a carrier (such as the bridge, flight control tower) are concentrated in a relatively small area called an *island*, a feature pioneered on HMS *Hermes* in 1923.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] While the island is usually built on the starboard side of the flight deck, the Japanese aircraft carriers *Akagi* and *Hiryū* had their islands built on the port side.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] Very few carriers have been designed or built without an island.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] The *flush deck* configuration proved to have significant drawbacks, primary of which was management of the exhaust from the power plant.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] Fumes coming across the deck were a major issue in USS *Langley*.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] In addition, lack of an island meant difficulties managing the flight deck, performing air traffic control, a lack of radar housing placements and problems with navigating and controlling the ship itself.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] Another deck structure that can be seen is a ski-jump ramp at the forward end of the flight deck.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] This was first developed to help launch short take off vertical landing (STOVL) aircraft take off at far higher weights than is possible with a vertical or rolling takeoff on flat decks.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] Originally developed by the Royal Navy, it since has been adopted by many navies for smaller carriers.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] A ski-jump ramp works by converting some of the forward rolling movement of the aircraft into vertical velocity and is sometimes combined with the aiming of jet thrust partly downward.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] This allows heavily loaded and fueled aircraft a few more precious seconds to attain sufficient air velocity and lift to sustain normal flight.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] Without a ski-jump, launching fully-loaded and fueled aircraft such as the Harrier would not be possible on a smaller flat deck ship before either stalling out or crashing directly into the sea.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] Although STOVL aircraft are capable of taking off vertically from a spot on the deck, using the ramp and a running start is far more fuel efficient and permits a heavier launch weight.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] As catapults are unnecessary, carriers with this arrangement reduce weight, complexity, and space needed for complex steam or electromagnetic launching equipment.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] Vertical landing aircraft also remove the need for arresting cables and related hardware.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] Russian, Chinese, and Indian carriers include a ski-jump ramp for launching lightly loaded conventional fighter aircraft but recover using traditional carrier arresting cables and a tailhook on their aircraft.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] For example, the Russian Sukhoi Su-33 is only able to launch from the carrier *Admiral Kuznetsov* with a minimal armament and fuel load.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] Another disadvantage is on mixed flight deck operations where helicopters are also present, such as on a US landing helicopter dock or landing helicopter assault amphibious assault ship.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p01] A ski jump is not included as this would eliminate one or more helicopter landing areas; this flat deck limits the loading of Harriers but is somewhat mitigated by the longer rolling start provided by a long flight deck compared to many STOVL carriers.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] The United States operates 11 nuclear-powered, catapult-assisted carriers, with a total combined deck space over twice that of all other nations combined as of 2016.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] China operates one catapult-assisted aircraft carrier and two ski-jump carriers.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] The United Kingdom and India each currently operate two ski-jump aircraft carriers, and France operates one nuclear-powered, catapult-assisted carrier.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] Russia deploys one ski-jump carrier, although it has not been operational since 2017.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] In addition, the US operates nine large amphibious assault ships with the capability to launch vertical/short takeoff and landing (V/STOL) aircraft, and China operates four amphibious assault ships of a similar size as helicopter carriers.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] Italy operates two light V/STOL carriers, and both Spain and Iran operate one V/STOL aircraft-carrying assault ship.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] Helicopter carriers are also operated by Japan (4, two converting to operate V/STOL fighters) France (3), Australia (2), Egypt (2), South Korea (2), Thailand (1), Brazil (1) and Iran (1).
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] Future aircraft carriers are under construction or planned by China, France, India, Italy, Russia, South Korea, and the US.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] The Royal Australian Navy operates two *Canberra*-class landing helicopter docks.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] The two-ship class, based on the Spanish vessel *Juan Carlos I* and built by Navantia and BAE Systems Australia, represents the largest ships ever built for the Royal Australian Navy.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] HMAS *Canberra* underwent sea trials in late 2013 and was commissioned in 2014.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] Her sister ship, HMAS *Adelaide*, was commissioned in December 2015.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] The Australian ships retain the ski-ramp from the *Juan Carlos I* design, although the RAN has not acquired carrier-based fixed-wing aircraft.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] In December 2017, the Brazilian Navy confirmed the purchase of HMS *Ocean* for (GBP) £84.6 million (equivalent to R$359.5M and US$113.2M) and renamed her *Atlântico*.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] The ship was decommissioned from Royal Navy service in March 2018.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] The Brazilian Navy commissioned the carrier on 29 June 2018 in the United Kingdom.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] After undertaking a period of maintenance in the UK, the ship travelled to its new home port, Rio de Janeiro Navy Arsenal (AMRJ) to be fully operational by 2020.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] Before leaving HMNB Devonport for her new homeport in Rio's AMRJ, *Atlântico* underwent operational sea training under the Royal Navy's Flag Officer Sea Training (FOST) program.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] China has had a long-term plan to operate six large aircraft carriers with two carriers per fleet.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] China is planning a class of eight LHD vessels, the Type 075 (NATO reporting name Yushen-class landing helicopter assault).
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] This is a class of amphibious assault ship under construction by the Hudong–Zhonghua Shipbuilding company.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] The first ship was commissioned in April 2021.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] China is also planning a modified class of the same concept, the Type 076 landing helicopter dock, that will be equipped with an electromagnetic catapult system and will likely support launching unmanned combat aerial vehicles.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] Egypt signed a contract with French shipbuilder DCNS to buy two *Mistral*-class helicopter carriers for approximately 950 million euros.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] The two ships were originally to be sold to Russia, but the deal was cancelled by France due to the Russian invasion of Ukraine in 2014.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] On 2 June 2016, Egypt received the first of two helicopter carriers acquired in October 2015, the landing helicopter dock *Gamal Abdel Nasser*.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] The flag transfer ceremony took place in the presence of Egyptian and French Navies' chiefs of staff, chairman and chief executive officers of both DCNS and STX France, and senior Egyptian and French officials.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] On 16 September 2016, DCNS delivered the second of two helicopter carriers, the landing helicopter dock *Anwar El Sadat* which also participated in a joint military exercise with the French Navy before arriving at her home port of Alexandria.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] The French Navy operates the 42,000-tonne nuclear-powered aircraft carrier, *Charles de Gaulle*.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] Commissioned in 2001, she is the flagship of the French Navy.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] The ship carries a complement of Dassault Rafale M and E-2C Hawkeye aircraft, EC725 Caracal and AS532 Cougar helicopters for combat search and rescue, as well as modern electronics and Aster missiles.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] She is a CATOBAR-type carrier that uses two 75 m C13-3 steam catapults of a shorter version of the catapult system installed on the US *Nimitz*-class carriers, one catapult at the bow and one across the front of the landing area.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] In addition, the French Navy operates three *Mistral*-class landing helicopter docks.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] In October 2018, the French Ministry of Defence began an 18-month €40 million study for the replacement of the French aircraft carrier *Charles de Gaulle* sometime after 2030.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] In December 2020, President Macron announced that construction of the next generation carrier would begin in around 2025 with sea trials to start in about 2036.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] The carrier is planned to have a displacement of around 75,000 tons and to carry about 32 next-generation fighters, two to three E-2D Advanced Hawkeyes and a yet-to-be-determined number of unmanned carrier air vehicles.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] India has plans for a third carrier, INS *Vishal*, also known as *Indigenous Aircraft Carrier 2 (IAC-2)* with a displacement of over 65,000 tonnes and is planned with a CATOBAR system to launch and recover heavier aircraft.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] India has also issued a request for information (RFI) to procure four Landing helicopter dock displacing 30,000–40,000 tons with a capacity to operate 12 medium lift special ops and two heavy lift helicopters and troops for amphibious operations.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] On February 6, 2025, the Islamic Revolutionary Guards Corps (IRGC) accepted the IRIS *Shahid Bagheri*, a 41,978-tonne drone UAV carrier converted from a container ship.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] was launched August 2013 and commissioned March 2015.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] the Japanese defense ministry's position is "We are not creating carrier air wings or carrier air squadrons" similar to the US Navy.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] from land bases; according to the 2020 Japanese Defense Ministry white paper the STOVL model was chosen for the JASDF due the lack of appropriately long runways to support air superiority capability across all of Japanese airspace.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] ships "for cooperation and advice on how to operate the fighter on the deck of the modified ships".
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] , marking 75 years since fixed-wing aircraft operated from a Japanese carrier.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] Portuguese Navy plans, for the second half of 2026, to receive the NRP *D.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] João II*, a platform ship capable of operating aerial, surface and underwater drones, medium helicopters (Sikorsky UH-60 Black Hawk) and heavy helicopters (EH101 Merlin) helicopters of the Portuguese Air Force.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] One STOBAR carrier: *Admiral Flota Sovetskogo Soyuza Kuznetsov*: 55,000-tonne *Kuznetsov*-class STOBAR aircraft carrier.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] Launched in 1985 as *Tbilisi*, renamed and operational from 1995.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] Without catapults she can launch and recover lightly fueled naval fighters for air defense or anti-ship missions but not heavy conventional bombing strikes.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] Officially designated an aircraft carrying cruiser, she is unique in carrying a heavy cruiser's complement of defensive weapons and large P-700 Granit offensive missiles.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] The P-700 systems will be removed in the coming refit to enlarge her below decks aviation facilities as well as upgrading her defensive systems.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] The ship has been out of service and in repairs since 2018.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] The most recent projection stated that repairs would be completed and the ship transferred back to the Russian Navy sometime in 2024, however this projection has not been met as of July 2025, and no updates have been provided.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] The Russian government has been considering the potential replacement of *Admiral Kuznetsov* for some time and has considered the Shtorm-class aircraft carrier as a possible option.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] This carrier will be a hybrid of CATOBAR and STOBAR, given the fact that she uses both systems of launching aircraft.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] The carrier is expected to cost between $1.8 billion and $5.63 billion.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] As of 2020, the project had not yet been approved and, given the financial costs, it was unclear whether it would be made a priority over other elements of Russian naval modernization.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] A class of 2 LHD, Project 23900 is planned and an official keel laying ceremony for the project happened on 20 July 2020.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] Two *Dokdo*-class 18,860-tonne full deck amphibious assault ships with hospital and well deck and facilities to serve as fleet flagships.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] South Korea had set tentative plans for procuring two light aircraft carriers by 2033, which would help make the ROKN a blue water navy.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] In December 2020, details of South Korea's planned carrier program (CVX) were finalized.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] A vessel of about 40,000 tons is envisaged carrying about 20 F-35B fighters as well as future maritime attack helicopters.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] Service entry had been anticipated in the early 2030s.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] In 2025 the program was cancelled and replaced with a drone carrier program.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] One offshore helicopter support ship: HTMS *Chakri Naruebet* helicopter carrier: 11,400-tonne STOVL carrier based on Spanish *Príncipe de Asturias* design.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] The AV-8S Matador/Harrier STOVL fighter wing, mostly inoperable by 1999, was retired from service without replacement in 2006.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] As of 2010, the ship is used for helicopter operations and for disaster relief.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] TCG *Anadolu* is a 27,079-tonne amphibious assault ship (LHD) (outfitted as drone carrier) of the Turkish Navy that can be configured as a 24,660-tonne V/STOL aircraft carrier.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] Construction began on 30 April 2016 by Sedef Shipbuilding Inc. at their Istanbul shipyard.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] TCG *Anadolu* was commissioned with a ceremony on 10 April 2023.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] The construction of a sister ship, to be named TCG *Trakya*, is currently being planned by the Turkish Navy.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] The Sikorsky S-70B Seahawk and the Bell AH-1 SuperCobra are the two main types of helicopters used on TCG *Anadolu*, with the occasional use of CH-47F Chinook helicopters of the Turkish Army during military exercises and operations.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] The AH-1W Super Cobras will eventually be complemented and replaced by the TAI T929 ATAK 2.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] The jet-powered, low-observable drone Bayraktar MIUS Kızılelma and the MALE UAV Bayraktar TB3 are two UCAVs that are specifically designed and manufactured by Baykar Technologies to be used on TCG *Anadolu*.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] The maiden flight of TAI Anka-3 (also part of Project MIUS), a jet-powered, flying wing type UCAV with stealth technology, was successfully completed on 28 December 2023.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] On 19 November 2024, Baykar Bayraktar TB3 UCAV successfully took-off from the flight deck of TCG *Anadolu* and landed on the ship.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] It was the first time a fixed-wing unmanned aircraft of this size and class had successfully landed on a short-runway landing helicopter dock, without the use of an arresting gear.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] On 3 January 2024, the Turkish government approved the plan for the design and construction of a larger aircraft carrier, named the *MUGEM*-class.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] On 15 February 2024, the Design and Projects Office of the Turkish Navy announced that it will be a STOBAR aircraft carrier with an overall length of 285 metres (935 ft), beam of 72 metres (236 ft), draught of 10.1 metres (33 ft), and displacement of 60,000 tons.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] It is to have a combined diesel–electric and gas (CODLAG) propulsion system and a maximum speed of more than 25 knots (29 mph; 46 km/h).
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] The construction of the first *MUGEM*-class aircraft carrier began on 2 January 2025.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] The first *MUGEM*-class aircraft carrier is being built at the Istanbul Naval Shipyard.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] Two 80,600-tonne (est. full load) *Queen Elizabeth*-class STOVL carriers which operate the F-35 Lightning II.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] HMS *Queen Elizabeth* was commissioned in December 2017 and HMS *Prince of Wales* in December 2019.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] The current US fleet of *Nimitz*-class carriers will be followed into service (and in some cases replaced) by the *Gerald R.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] It is expected that the ships will be more automated in an effort to reduce the amount of funding required to maintain and operate the vessels.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] The main new features are implementation of Electromagnetic Aircraft Launch System (EMALS) (which replaces the old steam catapults) and unmanned aerial vehicles.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] In terms of future carrier developments, Congress has discussed the possibility of accelerating the phasing-out of one or more *Nimitz*-class carriers, postponing or canceling the procurement of CVN-81 and CVN-82, or modifying the purchase contract.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] Following the deactivation of USS *Enterprise* in December 2012, the US fleet comprised 10 fleet carriers, but that number increased back to 11 with the commissioning of *Gerald R.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] The House Armed Services Seapower subcommittee on 24 July 2007, recommended seven or eight new carriers (one every four years).
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] However, the debate has deepened over budgeting for the $12–14.5 billion (plus $12 billion for development and research) for the 100,000-tonne *Gerald R.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] Ford*-class carrier (estimated service 2017) compared to the smaller $2 billion 45,000-tonne *America*-class amphibious assault ships, which are able to deploy squadrons of F-35Bs.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] The first of this class, USS *America*, is now in active service with another, USS *Tripoli*, and 9 more are planned.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] In a report to Congress in February 2018, the Navy stated it intends to maintain a "12 CVN force" as part of its 30-year acquisition plan.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] A few aircraft carriers have been preserved as museum ships.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] Aircraft carriers are prominently portrayed in a number of Hollywood films including *Midway* (2019) and the carrier USS *Nimitz* is centrally featured in the science fiction film *The Final Countdown* (1980).
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] The original film version about the Battle at Midway was made in England and titled *Midway* (1976).
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] Aircraft carriers are prominently featured in both *Top Gun* and *Top Gun: Maverick* as providing the launch sites and mission operations support for the fighter operations seen in both films.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] The Japanese aircraft carriers involved in the attack on Pearl Harbor are featured in the 1970 film *Tora!
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] Tora!* as well as the more recent film from 2001 *Pearl Harbor*.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] The carrier USS *Ronald Reagan* makes a cameo appearance at the end of the 2012 science fiction film *Battleship*.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] In the 2025 film *Mission: Impossible – The Final Reckoning*, the aircraft carrier USS *George Bush* is featured as delivering its special agent to a submarine rendezvous with the nuclear-powered USS *Ohio* in the Bering Straits by Alaska.
[src:brig/aircraft-carrier-p02] The 50-minute documentary titled *City of Steel: Carrier* was released by the Discovery Channel in 2000 covering the final months of building and inspecting the USS *Harry Truman* through its commissioning by President Bill Clinton.
[src:brig/aircraft-cruiser] The **aircraft cruiser** (also known as **aviation cruiser** or **cruiser-carrier**) is a warship that combines the features of the aircraft carrier and a surface warship such as a cruiser or battleship.
[src:brig/aircraft-cruiser] The first aircraft cruiser was originally a 1930s experimental concept of creating an all-around warship.
[src:brig/aircraft-cruiser] The early aircraft cruisers were usually armed with relatively heavy artillery, mines and a number of aircraft fitted with floats (making the ship a kind of seaplane tender/fighter catapult ship).
[src:brig/aircraft-cruiser] The early aircraft cruiser turned out to be an unsuccessful design.
[src:brig/aircraft-cruiser] The rapid development of naval aircraft in the 1930s quickly rendered the vessels obsolete, and they were rebuilt e.g. as anti-aircraft cruisers.
[src:brig/aircraft-cruiser] A United States design for a flight deck cruiser from 1930, was described as "a *Brooklyn*-class light cruiser forwards [and] one half of a *Wasp*-class aircraft carrier aft".
[src:brig/aircraft-cruiser] Although not built, similar ships were created during and after World War II as reconstructions and later from the keel up.
[src:brig/aircraft-cruiser] The Japanese built a pair of aircraft cruisers in 1937, the *Tone*-class cruisers.
[src:brig/aircraft-cruiser] These ships had their main armament of 4x twin 8" gun turrets placed forward of the superstructure, and an aircraft handling deck was built aft of the funnel.
[src:brig/aircraft-cruiser] The ships could carry a maximum of 8 float planes, launched by catapult, though the normal complement was 6.
[src:brig/aircraft-cruiser] During World War II, in part to offset the loss of carriers at the Battle of Midway, Japan rebuilt its *Ise*-class battleships as hybrid carriers, placing the flight deck and hangar aft to replace the rear turrets, while retaining their main guns forward and amidships.
[src:brig/aircraft-cruiser] The cruiser *Mogami* also had its rear gun turrets (which had been damaged at Midway) replaced by aircraft handling facilities.
[src:brig/aircraft-cruiser] The German *Kriegsmarine* also studied several "Flugdeckkreuzer" (flight deck cruiser) designs in 1942 which included 20.3 cm (8 inch) or 28 cm (11 inch) gun turrets forward of the flight deck.
[src:brig/aircraft-cruiser] A newer variation of the aircraft carrier is the helicopter carrier, which is capable of operating at least 4 or more helicopters, including medium and heavy lift models.
[src:brig/aircraft-cruiser] This is in contrast to surface warships such as cruisers, destroyers, and frigates which have basic aviation facilities, including a hangar and landing pad, that are sufficient only for 1–2 light/medium helicopters.
[src:brig/aircraft-cruiser] Post-war the United Kingdom reconstructed the *Tiger*-class cruisers HMS *Blake* and HMS *Tiger* into helicopter cruisers, retaining their guns forward but having their aft guns removed for the installation of a hangar and helicopter platform for the operation of four Sea King helicopters.
[src:brig/aircraft-cruiser] The Italian *Andrea Doria*-class cruisers and *Vittorio Veneto*, French *Jeanne d'Arc* and Soviet *Moskva*-class helicopter cruisers were built from the keel up as guided missile cruisers forward and helicopter carriers aft.
[src:brig/aircraft-cruiser] USS *Hayler* and her unnamed sister ship (which was never funded) were originally planned as modified *Spruance*-class destroyers, to be built as helicopter destroyers (DDH), provided they would not cost more than a standard *Spruance* class.
[src:brig/aircraft-cruiser] Litton-Ingalls completed sketch design work for *Hayler*, which moved the helicopter deck aft, stretching the length of the hangar and displacing the Sea Sparrow launcher to the top of the hangar.
[src:brig/aircraft-cruiser] The design would have accommodated two SH-3 Sea Kings or four smaller SH-60 Seahawk or SH-2 Seasprite helicopters.
[src:brig/aircraft-cruiser] While the prospective *Hayler* probably would not have cost much more to build than a standard *Spruance* class, the detail design and engineering work required before the ship could be built would have been substantial (similar work for the *Kidd* class cost $110.8 million).
[src:brig/aircraft-cruiser] This raised the cost of the DDH substantially above a standard *Spruance*-class destroyer.
[src:brig/aircraft-cruiser] While this additional cost might have been justified if the DDH was going to enter series production, it was difficult to justify for a single ship.
[src:brig/aircraft-cruiser] Accordingly, the Navy built *Hayler* to the same design as the rest of the *Spruance* class.
[src:brig/aircraft-cruiser] In 1980, there was a proposed “Interdiction Assault Ship” (IAS) conversion for the *Iowa*-class battleships that would have removed the aft main gun turret.
[src:brig/aircraft-cruiser] These aviation facilities could also support helicopters, SEAL teams and up to 500 Marines for an air assault.
[src:brig/aircraft-cruiser] In the empty space between the V flight deck would be up to 320 missile silos accommodating a mixture of Tomahawk land attack missiles, ASROC anti-submarine rockets and Standard surface-to-air missiles.
[src:brig/aircraft-cruiser] The existing 5-inch gun turrets would be replaced with 155-millimeter howitzers for naval gunfire support.
[src:brig/aircraft-cruiser] These modifications would have required significant time and funding to achieve so it was never carried out, furthermore the Department of Defense and the Navy wanted the *Iowa* battleships reactivated as quickly as possible.
[src:brig/aircraft-cruiser] In the Russian Navy, "aviation cruiser" is a designation for the *Kiev* and *Kuznetsov*-class ships.
[src:brig/aircraft-cruiser] They are a cross between a cruiser and an aircraft carrier.
[src:brig/aircraft-cruiser] Aviation cruisers have close-in weapon systems, both gun and missile, for self-defense against missiles or rockets.
[src:brig/aircraft-cruiser] Unlike aircraft carriers who rely solely upon their aircraft and helicopter complement for offensive power, aviation cruisers are also equipped with cruiser weaponry to engage the full gamut of surface, submarines and aircraft adversaries.
[src:brig/aircraft-cruiser] The *Kiev* class of aviation cruisers is capable of carrying VTOL aircraft and helicopters.
[src:brig/aircraft-cruiser] The ships have only a single angled flight deck for aviation.
[src:brig/aircraft-cruiser] The forward deck is used to carry cruiser weapons, including P-500 Bazalt cruise missiles that are the main armament of the *Slava*-class cruiser.
[src:brig/aircraft-cruiser] The *Kuznetsov* class is classified as heavy aviation cruisers, reflecting their greater weight as well as the larger number of aircraft they can operate.
[src:brig/aircraft-cruiser] In addition to helicopters, they are also capable of operating conventional fixed-wing aircraft like the Sukhoi Su-33 and the Mikoyan MiG-29K.
[src:brig/aircraft-cruiser] The ships have an angled flight deck as well as an axial flight deck for takeoff.
[src:brig/aircraft-cruiser] Since there is no catapult, a bow ski jump is used to assist takeoff.
[src:brig/aircraft-cruiser] *Kuznetsov* also carries the P-700 Granit cruise missiles that form the main armament of the *Kirov*-class battlecruiser.
[src:brig/aircraft-cruiser] All Soviet aircraft carriers were built at the Nikolayev Shipyard in the Ukrainian SSR.
[src:brig/aircraft-cruiser] Their classification as aircraft cruisers is very important for the purposes of international law, as it allows them to transit the Turkish Straits on their way into the Mediterranean Sea.
[src:brig/aircraft-cruiser] Under the Montreux Convention, aircraft carriers heavier than 15,000 tons may not pass through the Straits.
[src:brig/aircraft-cruiser] However, there is no tonnage limit on capital ships operated by Black Sea Powers.
[src:brig/aircraft-cruiser] Turkey has always allowed Soviet and Russian aviation cruisers to transit the Straits, and no other signatory to the Montreux Convention has challenged the ships' classification.
[src:brig/aircraft-cruiser] Some aircraft-carrying ships have been officially designated as cruisers, despite being for all intents and purposes light aircraft carriers.
[src:brig/aircraft-cruiser] The Royal Navy's *Invincible*-class aircraft carriers were originally termed "through-deck cruisers" for political reasons (the CVA-01 project had recently been cancelled).
[src:brig/aircraft-cruiser] In addition, they were expected to serve in some cruiser-like roles – taking on those roles from the RN's *Tiger*-class cruiser conversions – and were constructed in a similar fashion to cruisers.
[src:brig/aircraft-cruiser] Later in their life they were however known as aircraft carriers.
[src:brig/amenities-ship] An **amenities ship** was a naval vessel outfitted with recreational facilities as part of a mobile naval base.
[src:brig/amenities-ship] Amenities ships provided cinemas and canteens staffed by mercantile crews of the Royal Fleet Auxiliary.
[src:brig/amenities-ship] These ships were intended to provide a place where British Pacific Fleet personnel could relax between operations.
[src:brig/amenities-ship] As the Royal Navy prepared for operations in the Pacific Ocean during the final stage of World War II, it was recognised that warships would be operating far from base facilities.
[src:brig/amenities-ship] Mobile naval base facilities were prepared for remote Pacific harbours without shore facilities.
[src:brig/amenities-ship] Each mobile base would include repair ships and depot ships to provide maintenance and personnel services for flotillas of small ships like destroyers, submarines, minesweepers, and landing craft.
[src:brig/amenities-ship] Base ships were outfitted with offices to provide administrative and communications services for efficient refuelling and resupply of ships using the base, and accommodation ships provided living quarters for base staff and personnel awaiting transfer.
[src:brig/amenities-ship] Amenities ships were expected to provide an alternative to shore leave in remote locations without commercial recreation facilities.
[src:brig/amenities-ship] Two former minelayers, HMS *Agamemnon* and *Menestheus*, were converted to amenities ships after the Northern Barrage was completed.
[src:brig/amenities-ship] These 7,500-ton ships were former Blue Funnel Liners launched in 1929 and initially converted to auxiliary minelayers.
[src:brig/amenities-ship] They underwent further conversion at Vancouver in 1944 including installation of a brewery to make beer for shipboard consumption.
[src:brig/amenities-ship] These ships had been painted grey for service as North Atlantic minelayers, but were repainted white for service in the western Pacific.
[src:brig/amenities-ship] The war ended before they were used in their intended role as amenities ships.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] The **American Revolution** (1765–1789) was a political movement in the Thirteen Colonies of Great Britain.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] The movement began as a rebellion and evolved into a revolution resulting in the sovereign United States.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] These changes were the outcome of the associated American Revolutionary War (1775-1783).
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] The Second Continental Congress, as the provisional government, established the Continental Army and appointed George Washington as its commander-in-chief in 1775.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] The following year, the Congress passed the Lee Resolution on July 2nd, then unanimously adopted the Declaration of Independence on the Fourth of July.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] Throughout most of the war, the outcome appeared uncertain.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] The Constitution took effect in 1789 and the Bill of Rights was ratified in 1791.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] Discontent with colonial rule began shortly after the French and Indian War ended in 1763.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] Even though the colonies had fought in and supported the war directly with troops, funds and material, the British Parliament imposed new taxes to ostensibly compensate for wartime costs, and transferred control of the colonies' western lands to British officials in Montreal.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] Representatives from several colonies convened in New York City for the Stamp Act Congress in 1765; its "Declaration of Rights and Grievances" argued that this taxation without representation in Parliament and other policies violated their rights as Englishmen.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] In 1767, though the Stamp Act was repealed, tensions flared again following Parliament's passage of the Townshend Acts.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] In an effort to quell the mounting rebellion, King George III deployed British troops to the colony of Massachusetts, where they killed antagonists in the 1770 Boston Massacre.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] In December 1773, the local faction of the colonies-wide Sons of Liberty underground orchestrated the Boston Tea Party, during which they dumped chests of taxed tea owned by the British East India Company into Boston Harbor.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] Parliament responded by enacting a series of punitive laws, intended to end self-government in Massachusetts, but instead increased American support for the revolutionary cause.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] In 1774, twelve of the Thirteen Colonies sent delegates to the First Continental Congress; the Province of Georgia joined in 1775.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] The First Continental Congress began coordinating Patriot resistance through underground networks of committees largely built on the foundations of the Sons of Liberty network.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] In August 1775, King George III proclaimed Massachusetts to be in a state of rebellion.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] The British attempted to disarm the colonists, resulting in the Battles of Lexington and Concord, sparking the Revolutionary War.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] The Second Continental Congress convened in May of 1775 and created the Continental Army, which then surrounded Boston, forcing the British to withdraw by sea in March 1776 and leaving Patriots in control in every colony.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] In May 1776, Congress voted to suppress all forms of Crown authority, to be replaced by locally created authority, and each colony created a state constitution.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] On July 2, the Congress passed the Lee Resolution, affirming their support for joint independence.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] On July 4, 1776 they unanimously adopted the Declaration of Independence, famously proclaiming that "all men are created equal", having then evolved from a rebellion over British rights to a revolution based on universal rights.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] The Congress soon after began deliberating the Articles of Confederation, an effort to establish a multi-state self-governing coordinating body capable of negotiating international treaties and prosecuting the war.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] The Revolutionary War continued for another five years during which France ultimately entered, supporting the revolutionary cause.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] On September 28, 1781, Washington commanded the Continental Army's capture of a British army under General Cornwallis at the Siege of Yorktown, leading to the collapse of King George's control of Parliament.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] Consensus in Parliament soon shifted to the war ending on American terms.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] On September 3, 1783, the British signed the Treaty of Paris, recognizing the sovereign independence of the United States, and ceding to the new nation nearly all the territory east of the Mississippi River and south of the Great Lakes.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] The United States became the first nation to establish a federal republic with a written constitution based on the principles of universal natural rights, consent of the governed, and equality under the law, albeit with significant democratic limitations compared to later evolution of the concept.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] After the Glorious Revolution in Great Britain, it unofficially adopted a policy of "salutary neglect," whereby the Thirteen Colonies were largely left to govern themselves.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] This British policy reverted significantly after the French and Indian War.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] The British political establishment, especially after taking massive swaths of land from the former territories of New France, pursued a policy of greater control over colonial affairs, prompting the Thirteen Colonies to seek restoration of greater autonomy from Britain.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] After the American Revolution one Patriot, Capt.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] Levi Preston of Danvers, Massachusetts, who was asked why the Americans rebelled against England, responded: "...we always had governed ourselves, and we always meant to.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] The Thirteen Colonies were established in the 17th century as part of the English Empire and became parts of the British Empire after the union of England and Scotland in 1707.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] The development of a unique American identity can be traced to the English Civil War (1642–1651) and its aftermath.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] In that period the Puritan colonies of New England supported the Commonwealth government responsible for the execution of King Charles I.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] After the Stuart Restoration of 1660, Massachusetts did not recognize Charles II as the legitimate king for more than a year after his coronation.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] In King Philip's War (1675–1678), the New England colonies fought a coalition of a few Native American tribes without military assistance from England, thereby contributing to the development of a uniquely American identity separate from that of the British people.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] In the 1680s, Charles and his brother, James II, attempted to bring New England under direct English control.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] The colonists fiercely opposed this, and the Crown nullified their colonial charters in response.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] In 1686, James finalized these efforts by consolidating the separate New England colonies along with New York and New Jersey into the Dominion of New England.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] Edmund Andros was appointed royal governor and tasked with governing the new Dominion under his direct rule.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] Colonial assemblies and town meetings were restricted, new local taxes were levied, and rights were abridged.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] Dominion rule triggered bitter resentment throughout New England.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] When James tried to rule without Parliament, the English aristocracy removed him from power in the Glorious Revolution of 1688.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] This was followed by the 1689 Boston revolt, which overthrew Dominion rule.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] Colonial governments reasserted their control after the revolt.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] The new monarchs, William and Mary, granted new charters to the individual New England colonies.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] After the Glorious Revolution, the British Empire became a constitutional monarchy with sovereignty in the King-in-Parliament.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] Aristocrats inherited seats in the House of Lords, while the gentry and merchants controlled the elected House of Commons.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] The king ruled through cabinet ministers who depended on majority support in the Commons to govern effectively.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] British subjects on both sides of the Atlantic proudly claimed that the unwritten British constitution, with its guarantees of the rights of Englishmen, protected personal liberty better than any other government.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] The British constitution served as the model for colonial governments.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] The Crown appointed a royal governor in each colony to exercise executive power, usually also appointing a Governor's Council largely to act as an unelected upper chamber of the legislature.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] Property owners elected a colonial assembly amongst themselves with powers to legislate and levy taxes, but the British government reserved the right to veto colonial legislation.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] The British government lacked the resources and information necessary for close supervision of the colonies.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] Instead, British officials negotiated and compromised with colonial leaders to gain compliance with imperial policies.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] The colonies defended themselves with provincial troops and colonial militias of locals, and the British government rarely sent military forces to America before 1755.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] According to historian Robert Middlekauff, "Americans had become almost completely self-governing" before the American Revolution, a practice that was consistent with the British monarchy's practice of salutary neglect.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] With little industry except shipbuilding, the colonies exported agricultural products in return for manufactured goods.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] They also imported molasses, rum, and sugar from the British West Indies.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] In 1651, Parliament passed the first in a series of Navigation Acts, which restricted colonial trade with foreign countries.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] The British government pursued this policy of mercantilism in order to grow its economic and political power.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] According to mercantilism, the colonies existed for the mother country's economic benefit, and the colonists' economic needs were largely inconsequential.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] The Thirteen Colonies could trade with the rest of the empire but only ship certain commodities like tobacco to Britain.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] Any European imports bound for British America had to first pass through an English port and pay customs duties.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] Other laws regulated the developing colonial industries to prevent competition with industries in Britain, such as the Wool Act 1698, the Hat Act 1731, and the Iron Act 1750.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] Colonial reactions to these policies were mixed.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] The Molasses Act 1733, for example, placed a duty of six pence per gallon upon foreign molasses imported into the colonies.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] This act was particularly egregious to the New England colonists, who protested it as unconstitutional taxation without representation in the British parliament.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] The act increased the smuggling of foreign molasses, and the British government ceased enforcement efforts after the 1740s.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] On the other hand, certain merchants and local industries benefited from the restrictions on foreign competition.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] The limits on foreign-built ships greatly benefited the colonial shipbuilding industry, particularly in New England.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] Some argue that the economic impact was minimal on the colonists, but the political friction that the acts triggered was more serious, as the merchants most directly affected were also the most politically active.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] During the French and Indian War (1754–1763), the British government fielded 45,000 soldiers, half British Regulars and half colonial volunteers.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] The colonies also contributed funds and materiel to the war effort; though, two-fifths of this spending was reimbursed by the British government.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] Great Britain defeated France and acquired that nation's territory east of the Mississippi River.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] In order to allow approximately 1,500 politically well-connected British Army officers to remain on active duty in America with full pay after the war, the Bute ministry decided in early 1763 to permanently garrison 10,000 soldiers in North America.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] Due to long-established English resistance to a standing army, stationing these officers in Great Britain during peacetime was a politically unacceptable alternative.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] The excuse made for a standing army in America was defense against French troops stationed in the West Indies, and foreign populations in newly acquired territories (the French in Canada and the Spanish in Florida).
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] In addition, British soldiers were supposed to help collect customs duties and prevent colonists from instigating conflict with Native Americans.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] Instead, increased British migration beyond the Appalachian Mountains and Native American anger over the policies of General Jeffery Amherst caused Pontiac's War (1763–1766).
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] In response, the Grenville ministry issued the Royal Proclamation of 1763, designating the territory between the Appalachian Mountains and the Mississippi River an Indian Reserve closed to colonial settlement.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] The Proclamation angered settlers, fur traders, and land speculators; however, it failed to stop westward migration.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] Stationing troops in North America on a permanent basis would cost another £360,000 a year.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] On a per capita basis, Grenville claimed Americans paid 1 shilling in taxes directly to the empire (not including local taxes) compared to 26 shillings paid by the English.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] The enslaved, a near majority of the population in some colonies, did not pay any taxes and therefore skewed this comparison.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] On March 9, 1764, Grenville proposed the Sugar Act, which was enacted by Parliament in April.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] It lowered the duty on foreign molasses from 6 pence to 3 pence per gallon.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] The Treasury believed it would generate £78,000.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] To ensure this money could be collected, the act strengthened efforts against smuggling.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] Customs officials could choose whether to prosecute violators in colonial courts or vice admiralty courts.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] Unlike colonial courts where there was a presumption of innocence and cases were decided by local juries who frequently acquitted accused smugglers, vice admiralty courts operated on a presumption of guilt and cases were decided by Crown-appointed judges.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] On the same day he introduced the Sugar Act in Parliament, Grenville stated it might be necessary to levy stamp duties on the colonies to raise additional revenue, but he delayed action to give the colonies time to propose another way to raise the revenue.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] Parliament passed the Stamp Act in March 1765, which imposed direct taxes on the colonies for the first time.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] All official documents, newspapers, almanacs, and pamphlets were required to have the stamps—even decks of playing cards.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] The colonists did not object that the taxes were high; they were actually low.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] They objected to their lack of representation in the Parliament, which gave them no voice concerning legislation that affected them, such as the tax, thereby violating the unwritten English constitution.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] This grievance was overly simplified with the slogan "No taxation without representation".
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] Shortly following adoption of the Stamp Act, factions of the Sons of Liberty formed in each colony, and began using public demonstrations, boycotts, and threats of violence to ensure that the offending British policies became unenforceable.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] In Boston, the Sons of Liberty burned the records of the vice admiralty court and looted the home of chief justice Thomas Hutchinson.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] Several legislatures called for united action, and nine colonies sent delegates to the Stamp Act Congress in New York City in October.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] Moderates led by John Dickinson drew up a Declaration of Rights and Grievances stating in part that the colonists were equal to all other British subjects and that, among other abuses, taxes passed without representation in Parliament violated their rights as Englishmen.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] The Parliament at Westminster saw itself as the supreme lawmaking authority throughout the Empire and thus entitled to enact any legislation, including levying any tax, without colonial approval or even consultation.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] They argued that the colonies were legally British corporations subordinate to the British Parliament.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] Parliament insisted that the colonists effectively enjoyed a "virtual representation", as most British people did, since only a small minority of the British population were eligible to elect representatives to Parliament.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] However, Americans such as James Otis maintained that there was no one in Parliament responsible specifically to any colonial constituency, so they were not "virtually represented" by anyone in Parliament.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] The Rockingham government came to power in July 1765, and Parliament debated whether to repeal the stamp tax or to send an army to enforce it.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] Benjamin Franklin appeared before them to make the case for repeal, explaining that the colonies had spent heavily in manpower, money, and blood defending the empire, and that further taxes to pay for those wars were unjust and might bring about a rebellion.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] Parliament agreed and repealed the tax on February 21, 1766, but they insisted in the Declaratory Act of March 1766 that they retained full power to make laws for the colonies "in all cases whatsoever".
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] The repeal nonetheless caused widespread celebrations in the colonies.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] In 1767, the British Parliament passed the Townshend Acts, which placed duties on several staple goods, including paper, glass, and tea, and established a Board of Customs in Boston to more rigorously execute trade regulations.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] The new taxes were enacted on the belief that Americans only objected to internal taxes and not to external taxes such as custom duties.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] John Dickinson however, in his widely read pamphlet *Letters from a Farmer in Pennsylvania*, argued against the constitutionality of the acts because their purpose was to raise revenue and not to regulate trade.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] Colonists responded to the taxes by organizing new boycotts of British goods.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] These boycotts were less effective, however, as the goods taxed by the Townshend Acts were widely used.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] In February 1768, the Assembly of Massachusetts Bay Colony issued a circular letter to the other colonies urging them to coordinate resistance.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] The governor dissolved the assembly when it refused to rescind the letter.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] In June 1768 a riot broke out in Boston over the seizure of the sloop *Liberty*, owned by John Hancock, for alleged smuggling.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] Customs officials were forced to flee, prompting the British to deploy troops to Boston.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] A Boston town meeting declared that no obedience was due to parliamentary laws and called for the convening of a convention.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] A convention assembled but only issued a mild protest before dissolving itself.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] In January 1769, Parliament responded to the unrest by reactivating the Treason Act 1543 which called for subjects outside the realm to face trials for treason in England.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] The governor of Massachusetts was instructed to collect evidence of said treason, and the threat caused widespread outrage, though it was not carried out.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] On March 5, 1770, a large crowd gathered around a group of British soldiers on a Boston street.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] The crowd grew threatening, throwing snowballs, rocks, and debris at them.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] There was no order to fire, but the soldiers panicked and fired into the crowd.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] They hit 11 people; three civilians died of wounds at the scene of the shooting, and two died shortly after.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] The event quickly came to be called the Boston Massacre.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] The soldiers were tried and acquitted (defended by American patriot John Adams), but the widespread descriptions soon began to turn colonial sentiment against the British.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] This accelerated the downward spiral in the relationship between Britain and the province of Massachusetts, and other colonies were becoming increasingly empathetic.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] A new ministry under Lord North came to power in 1770, and Parliament repealed most of the Townshend duties, except the tax on tea.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] This temporarily resolved the crisis, and the boycott of British goods largely ceased, with only the more radical patriots such as Samuel Adams continuing to agitate.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] In June 1772, American patriots, including John Brown, burned a British warship that had been vigorously enforcing unpopular trade regulations, in what became known as the *Gaspee* Affair.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] The affair was investigated for possible treason, but no action was taken.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] In 1773, private letters were published in which Massachusetts Governor Thomas Hutchinson claimed that the colonists could not enjoy all English liberties, and in which Lieutenant Governor Andrew Oliver called for the direct payment of colonial officials, which had been paid by local authorities.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] This would have reduced the influence of colonial representatives over their government.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] The letters' contents were used as evidence of a systematic plot against American rights, and discredited Hutchinson in the eyes of the people; the colonial Assembly petitioned for his recall.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] Benjamin Franklin, postmaster general for the colonies, acknowledged that he leaked the letters, which led to him being removed from his position.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] From Boston Samuel Adams set about creating new Committees of Correspondence, built largely on the foundations of the underground Sons of Liberty network, linking Patriots in all 13 colonies and eventually providing the framework for a provisional government.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] Virginia, the largest colony, set up its Committee of Correspondence in early 1773, on which Patrick Henry and Thomas Jefferson served.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] A total of about 7,000 to 8,000 Patriots served on these Committees; Loyalists were excluded.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] The committees became the leaders of the American resistance to British actions, and later largely determined the war effort at the state and local level.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] When the First Continental Congress resolved to boycott British products, the colonial and local Committees took charge, examining merchant records and publishing the names of merchants who attempted to defy the boycott by importing British goods.
[src:brig/american-revolution-p01] Meanwhile, Parliament passed the Tea Act lowering the price of taxed tea exported to the colonies, to help the British East India Company undersell smuggled untaxed Dutch tea.
